{"title_page": "The Olde Pink House", "text_new": "{{Infobox building\n| name       = The Olde Pink House\n| native_name= The Pink House\n| former_names        = Habersham House\n| image               = File:Olde_Pink_House.jpeg\n| caption             = The Olde Pink House in 2017\n| map_type            = \n| building_type       = \n| architectural_style = [[Georgian architecture|Georgian]]\n| structural_system   = \n| cost                = \n| location            = [[Savannah, Georgia|Savannah]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], [[United States]]\n| address             = 23 Abercorn Street\n| client              = \n| owner               =\n| current_tenants     = \n| landlord            = \n| coordinates         = {{coord|32.079672|-81.089792|display=inline,title}}\n| start_date          = 1771\n| completion_date     = {{Start date and age|1789}}\n| inauguration_date   = \n| demolition_date     = \n| destruction_date    = \n| height              = \n| diameter            = \n| other_dimensions    = \n| floor_count         = 3\n| floor_area          = ~16,000 sq. ft<ref>[https://www.savannahnow.com/news/20181228/savannahs-olde-pink-house-damaged-but-not-done-after-fire-says-management \"Savannah\u2019s Olde Pink House damaged, but not done after fire, says management\"] - SavannahNow.com, December 28, 2018</ref>\n| main_contractor     = \n| architect           = Joseph Clay<ref>[https://www.loc.gov/item/2017886332/ \"Habersham house, 25 Abercorn Street, Savannah, Chatham County, Georgia\"] - [[Library of Congress]]</ref> (original);<br />Mark P. Finlay Architects (2006 expansion)<ref>[http://markfinlay.com/olde-pink-house-commercial Olde Pink House] - MarkFinlay.com</ref>\n| structural_engineer = \n| services_engineer   = \n| civil_engineer      = \n| other_designers     = \n| quantity_surveyor   = \n| awards              = \n| references          = \n}}\n\n'''The Olde Pink House''' (also known as '''The Pink House''' and the '''Habersham House''') is a restaurant and tavern in [[Savannah, Georgia]], United States. Located on Abercorn Street, in the northwestern [[Land lot|trust lot]] of [[Squares of Savannah, Georgia#Reynolds Square|Reynolds Square]], the building dates from 1771. It is bounded by East Bryan Street to the north, Abercorn Street to the east and East Saint Julian Street to the south.\n\nOne of its key features is a [[Palladian]] window above the portico.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Habersham house, 25 Abercorn Street, Savannah, Chatham County, Georgia.jpg|thumb|left|The building when it was Alida Harper Fowlkes' Georgian Tea Room during the 1930s and '40s. The portico and the section just visible to the right were added around 1820. Photographed by [[Frances Benjamin Johnston]].]]\n\nThe building was originally known, when it was built in 1789, as Habersham House, after its owner, James Habersham, Jr. (1745\u20131799; son of [[James Habersham]]), one of Savannah's most important early cotton factors and founding-family members. Habersham lived there until his death in 1799.<ref name=history>[https://static1.squarespace.com/static/59a7470e6f4ca3ff9e4ef513/t/5b86f7a40e2e7266ba8b765a/1535571878672/OPH+History+and+Menu.pdf The Olde Pink House history] - www.theoldepinkhouse.com</ref><ref name=history2>[https://www.savannahnow.com/article/20081023/news/310239845 The Olde Pink House: James Habersham\u2019s real resting place] - SavannahNow.com, October 23, 2008</ref> The lot was originally a land grant from the [[British Crown]]. It survived the Savannah fire of 1796 that destroyed 229 buildings in the city.<ref name=fire/><ref>{{Citation |publisher = S. Hall, and Thomas & Andrews |publication-place = Boston |author = [[Jedidiah Morse]] |title = American Gazetteer |publication-date = 1797 |chapter=Savannah |chapterurl= https://archive.org/stream/americangazettee00mors#page/n497/mode/2up\n| ref = {{harvid|Morse|1797}}\n}}</ref>\n\nIn 1812, the home became Planters Bank, the first bank in Georgia.<ref name=history/> It was at this time that a [[portico]], supported by unfluted [[Doric order|Doric]] columns, was added to the building's main fa\u00e7ade, while an extension was built on the northern side.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ujpjGQVt9r0 \"200 Years of William Jay Architecture\"] - Telfair Museums, August 23, 2019</ref>\n\nAfter the [[American Civil War|Civil War]], the house changed hands several times, becoming an attorney's office, bookstore and (between 1930 and 1943) Alida Harper Fowlkes' (1908\u20131985) Georgian Tea Room.<ref>[http://ghs.galileo.usg.edu/ghs/view?docId=ead/MS%202178-ead.xml \"Alida Harper Fowlkes papers\"] - Georgia Historical Society</ref><ref name=history/>\n\nThe building was bought and restored by [[James Arthur Williams|Jim Williams]], owner of the [[Mercer House (Savannah, Georgia)|Mercer House]], in the middle of the 20th century.<ref>[https://www.blufftontoday.com/news/20200117/30-years-after-death-of-jim-williams-his-iconic-savannah-home-is-being-restored \"30 years after death of Jim Williams, his iconic Savannah home is being restored\"] - Bluffon Today, January 17, 2020</ref>\n\nIn 1970, Herschel McCallar, Jr. and his partner Jeffrey Keith bought the building for around $60,000. It opened as a restaurant in 1971.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jOHiEZZNJcA \"The Olde Pink House re-opens\"] - WSAV3, April 8, 2019</ref>\n\nKeith sold it to the William Balish family in 1992, two years after the death of McCallar.<ref>[https://www.wtoc.com/2018/12/27/first-responders-scene-fire-olde-pink-house-savannah/ \"The Olde Pink House striving to reopen as soon as possible after fire\"] - WTOC, December 27 2018</ref> The Balishes restored it to its original grandeur.<ref name=history/>\n\nIn 2006, Arches Bar, on the southern side of the building, was added during an expansion project.<ref>[https://www.savannahnow.com/article/20060712/NEWS/307129882 \"The Olde Pink House Restaurant resumes construction of addition\"] - SavannahNow.com, July 12, 2006</ref> There is also a cellar tavern, Planters Tavern, which features a single-table wine vault for special occasions.\n\nIn December 2018, a fire broke out in the upstairs ballroom, causing damage that resulted in the building closing for four months.<ref name=fire>[https://www.savannahnow.com/news/20181227/savannah-restaurants-rally-to-help-employees-after-olde-pink-house-fire \"Savannah restaurants rally to help employees after Olde Pink House fire\"] - SavannahNow.com, December 27, 2018</ref><ref>[https://www.savannahnow.com/business/20190126/savannahs-olde-pink-house-announces-reopening-plan \"Savannah\u2019s Olde Pink House announces reopening plan\"] - SavannahNow.com, January 26, 2019</ref>\n\n==Copy==\n[[File:102 East Gaston Street, Savannah, Georgia.jpg|thumb|102 East Gaston Street, sometime after 1928.]]\n\nAn almost-identical house was built in 1928<ref>[https://www.trulia.com/p/ga/savannah/102-e-gaston-st-savannah-ga-31401--2092359961 102 E Gaston Street] - Trulia.com</ref> at 102 East Gaston Street,<ref>[https://www.google.com/maps/@32.0699105,-81.0939161,3a,75y,15.27h,94.89t/data=!3m6!1e1!3m4!1si8nfO4jyjrPq0mzsb7E-tg!2e0!7i13312!8i6656 102 East Gaston Street] - [[Google Street View]]</ref> just beyond the northeastern corner of [[Forsyth Park]]. A photograph of it, minus the two triangular roof vents that were added later, in the archives of the [[Library of Congress]] erroneously lists it as being Habersham House.<ref>[https://www.loc.gov/resource/hhh.ga0023.photos/?sp=7 7. Historic American Buildings Survey L. D. Andrew Photographer Dec. 30, 1936 FRONT ELEVATION - Habersham House, Reynolds Square Vicinity, Savannah, Chatham County, GA] - LOC.gov</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Habersham House, Savannah.jpg|Southeast corner\nFile:Habersham House, Reynolds Square 2.jpg|A close-up of the portico\nFile:Arches_Bar.jpeg|Arches Bar, located on the first floor on the building's southern side, was part of a 2006 expansion\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|45em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.theoldepinkhouserestaurant.com The Olde Pink House official website]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Olde Pink House, The}}\n[[Category:Landmarks in Savannah, Georgia]]\n[[Category:Houses in Savannah, Georgia]]\n[[Category:Restaurants in Savannah, Georgia]]\n[[Category:Taverns in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Houses completed in 1789]]\n[[Category:Georgian architecture in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Palladian Revival architecture in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox building\n| name       = The Olde Pink House\n| native_name= The Pink House\n| former_names        = Habersham House\n| image               = File:Olde_Pink_House.jpeg\n| caption             = The Olde Pink House in 2017\n| map_type            = \n| building_type       = \n| architectural_style = [[Georgian architecture|Georgian]]\n| structural_system   = \n| cost                = \n| location            = [[Savannah, Georgia|Savannah]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], [[United States]]\n| address             = 23 Abercorn Street\n| client              = \n| owner               =\n| current_tenants     = \n| landlord            = \n| coordinates         = {{coord|32.079672|-81.089792|display=inline,title}}\n| start_date          = 1771\n| completion_date     = {{Start date and age|1789}}\n| inauguration_date   = \n| demolition_date     = \n| destruction_date    = \n| height              = \n| diameter            = \n| other_dimensions    = \n| floor_count         = 3\n| floor_area          = ~16,000 sq. ft<ref>[https://www.savannahnow.com/news/20181228/savannahs-olde-pink-house-damaged-but-not-done-after-fire-says-management \"Savannah\u2019s Olde Pink House damaged, but not done after fire, says management\"] - SavannahNow.com, December 28, 2018</ref>\n| main_contractor     = \n| architect           = Joseph Clay<ref>[https://www.loc.gov/item/2017886332/ \"Habersham house, 25 Abercorn Street, Savannah, Chatham County, Georgia\"] - [[Library of Congress]]</ref> (original);<br />Mark P. Finlay Architects (2006 expansion)<ref>[http://markfinlay.com/olde-pink-house-commercial Olde Pink House] - MarkFinlay.com</ref>\n| structural_engineer = \n| services_engineer   = \n| civil_engineer      = \n| other_designers     = \n| quantity_surveyor   = \n| awards              = \n| references          = \n}}\n\n'''The Olde Pink House''' (also known as '''The Pink House''' and the '''Habersham House''') is a restaurant and tavern in [[Savannah, Georgia]], United States. Located on Abercorn Street, in the northwestern [[Land lot|trust lot]] of [[Squares of Savannah, Georgia#Reynolds Square|Reynolds Square]], the building dates from 1771. It is bounded by East Bryan Street to the north, Abercorn Street to the east and East Saint Julian Street to the south.\n\nOne of its key features is a [[Palladian]] window above the portico.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Habersham house, 25 Abercorn Street, Savannah, Chatham County, Georgia.jpg|thumb|left|The building when it was Alida Harper Fowlkes' Georgian Tea Room during the 1930s and '40s. The portico and the section just visible to the right were added around 1820. Photographed by [[Frances Benjamin Johnston]].]]\n\nThe building was originally known, when it was built in 1789, as Habersham House, after its owner, James Habersham, Jr. (1745\u20131799; son of [[James Habersham]]), one of Savannah's most important early cotton factors and founding-family members. Habersham lived there until his death in 1799.<ref name=history>[https://static1.squarespace.com/static/59a7470e6f4ca3ff9e4ef513/t/5b86f7a40e2e7266ba8b765a/1535571878672/OPH+History+and+Menu.pdf The Olde Pink House history] - www.theoldepinkhouse.com</ref><ref name=history2>[https://www.savannahnow.com/article/20081023/news/310239845 The Olde Pink House: James Habersham\u2019s real resting place] - SavannahNow.com, October 23, 2008</ref> The lot was originally a land grant from the [[British Crown]]. It survived the Savannah fire of 1796 that destroyed 229 buildings in the city.<ref name=fire/><ref>{{Citation |publisher = S. Hall, and Thomas & Andrews |publication-place = Boston |author = [[Jedidiah Morse]] |title = American Gazetteer |publication-date = 1797 |chapter=Savannah |chapterurl= https://archive.org/stream/americangazettee00mors#page/n497/mode/2up\n| ref = {{harvid|Morse|1797}}\n}}</ref>\n\nIn 1812, the home became Planters Bank, the first bank in Georgia, and housed the monies of all the colonists.<ref name=history/> It was at this time that a [[portico]], supported by unfluted [[Doric order|Doric]] columns, was added to the building's main fa\u00e7ade, while an extension was built on the northern side.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ujpjGQVt9r0 \"200 Years of William Jay Architecture\"] - Telfair Museums, August 23, 2019</ref>\n\nAfter the [[American Civil War|Civil War]], the house changed hands several times, becoming an attorney's office, bookstore and (between 1930 and 1943) Alida Harper Fowlkes' (1908\u20131985) Georgian Tea Room.<ref>[http://ghs.galileo.usg.edu/ghs/view?docId=ead/MS%202178-ead.xml \"Alida Harper Fowlkes papers\"] - Georgia Historical Society</ref><ref name=history/>\n\nThe building was bought and restored by [[James Arthur Williams|Jim Williams]], owner of the [[Mercer House (Savannah, Georgia)|Mercer House]], in the middle of the 20th century.<ref>[https://www.blufftontoday.com/news/20200117/30-years-after-death-of-jim-williams-his-iconic-savannah-home-is-being-restored \"30 years after death of Jim Williams, his iconic Savannah home is being restored\"] - Bluffon Today, January 17, 2020</ref>\n\nIn 1970, Herschel McCallar, Jr. and his partner Jeffrey Keith bought the building for around $60,000. It opened as a restaurant in 1971.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jOHiEZZNJcA \"The Olde Pink House re-opens\"] - WSAV3, April 8, 2019</ref>\n\nKeith sold it to the William Balish family in 1992, two years after the death of McCallar.<ref>[https://www.wtoc.com/2018/12/27/first-responders-scene-fire-olde-pink-house-savannah/ \"The Olde Pink House striving to reopen as soon as possible after fire\"] - WTOC, December 27 2018</ref> The Balishes restored it to its original grandeur.<ref name=history/>\n\nIn 2006, Arches Bar, on the southern side of the building, was added during an expansion project.<ref>[https://www.savannahnow.com/article/20060712/NEWS/307129882 \"The Olde Pink House Restaurant resumes construction of addition\"] - SavannahNow.com, July 12, 2006</ref> There is also a cellar tavern, Planters Tavern, which features a single-table wine vault for special occasions.\n\nIn December 2018, a fire broke out in the upstairs ballroom, causing damage that resulted in the building closing for four months.<ref name=fire>[https://www.savannahnow.com/news/20181227/savannah-restaurants-rally-to-help-employees-after-olde-pink-house-fire \"Savannah restaurants rally to help employees after Olde Pink House fire\"] - SavannahNow.com, December 27, 2018</ref><ref>[https://www.savannahnow.com/business/20190126/savannahs-olde-pink-house-announces-reopening-plan \"Savannah\u2019s Olde Pink House announces reopening plan\"] - SavannahNow.com, January 26, 2019</ref>\n\n==Copy==\n[[File:102 East Gaston Street, Savannah, Georgia.jpg|thumb|102 East Gaston Street, sometime after 1928.]]\n\nAn almost-identical house was built in 1928<ref>[https://www.trulia.com/p/ga/savannah/102-e-gaston-st-savannah-ga-31401--2092359961 102 E Gaston Street] - Trulia.com</ref> at 102 East Gaston Street,<ref>[https://www.google.com/maps/@32.0699105,-81.0939161,3a,75y,15.27h,94.89t/data=!3m6!1e1!3m4!1si8nfO4jyjrPq0mzsb7E-tg!2e0!7i13312!8i6656 102 East Gaston Street] - [[Google Street View]]</ref> just beyond the northeastern corner of [[Forsyth Park]]. A photograph of it, minus the two triangular roof vents that were added later, in the archives of the [[Library of Congress]] erroneously lists it as being Habersham House.<ref>[https://www.loc.gov/resource/hhh.ga0023.photos/?sp=7 7. Historic American Buildings Survey L. D. Andrew Photographer Dec. 30, 1936 FRONT ELEVATION - Habersham House, Reynolds Square Vicinity, Savannah, Chatham County, GA] - LOC.gov</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Habersham House, Savannah.jpg|Southeast corner\nFile:Habersham House, Reynolds Square 2.jpg|A close-up of the portico\nFile:Arches_Bar.jpeg|Arches Bar, located on the first floor on the building's southern side, was part of a 2006 expansion\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|45em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.theoldepinkhouserestaurant.com The Olde Pink House official website]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Olde Pink House, The}}\n[[Category:Landmarks in Savannah, Georgia]]\n[[Category:Houses in Savannah, Georgia]]\n[[Category:Restaurants in Savannah, Georgia]]\n[[Category:Taverns in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Houses completed in 1789]]\n[[Category:Georgian architecture in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Palladian Revival architecture in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n", "name_user": "Seasider53", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Olde_Pink_House"}
{"title_page": "Upper Chapel", "text_new": "{{for|the hamlet in Wales|Upper Chapel, Powys}}\n\n{{Infobox religious building |building_name=Upper Chapel |image=Upper Chapel Sheffield.JPG | caption=Facade of the Upper Chapel | location=[[Sheffield City Centre]]<br>[[South Yorkshire]], [[England]] | map_type=Sheffield\n|geo = {{coord|53.3808|-1.4683|display=inline,title}}\n|religious_affiliation=[[Unitarianism|Unitarian]] |district= |consecration_year= |status= |leadership= |website= |architect= |architecture_type=[[Church (building)|Church]] |architecture_style= |facade_direction= |year_completed=1700 |construction_cost= |capacity= |length= |width= |width_nave= |height_max= |dome_quantity= |dome_height_outer= |dome_height_inner= |dome_dia_outer= |dome_dia_inner= |minaret_quantity= |minaret_height= |spire_quantity= |spire_height= |materials=Brick }}\n\n'''Upper Chapel''' is a [[Unitarianism|Unitarian]] [[chapel]] on Norfolk Street in [[Sheffield City Centre]]. It is a member of the [[General Assembly of Unitarian and Free Christian Churches]], the [[umbrella organisation]] for British Unitarians.<ref>{{Citation | url = http://www.unitarian.org.uk/findcong.shtml?cong=Sheffield%20Norfolk%20Street| title = Find a Congregation: Sheffield| accessdate = 23 January 2011| publisher = The General Assembly of Unitarian and Free Christian Churches (Great Britain)}}</ref> The Chapel is [[Grade II listed]].<ref name=\"chapel\" />\n\nJames Fisher was the vicar at [[Sheffield Parish Church]] during the [[Commonwealth of England]].  He was expelled in the [[Great Ejection]] for refusing to sign the [[Act of Uniformity 1662]], and around a tenth of his parishioners followed him in becoming [[Rational dissenter|Dissenter]]s.<ref name=\"pevsner\">Ruth Harman and John Minnis, ''Pevsner Architectural Guides: Sheffield''</ref>\n\nSeveral splits ensued, but by the 1690s, the dominant group of non-conformists was led by [[Timothy Jollie]].  His congregation constructed Upper Chapel<ref>\"Jollie, Timothy\", ''[[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]]''</ref> as the first [[Nonconformist (Protestantism)|non-conformist]] chapel in Sheffield [[1700 in architecture|in 1700]].<ref name=\"pevsner\" />  It was built of brick and faced on to [[Fargate]].  The chapel originally boasted a congregation of about 1,000 people, a sixth of the city's population.<ref name=\"chapel\">[http://www.upperchapel.org.uk/w/doku.php/uc:history Upper Chapel: History]</ref>  The side walls survive from this period.<ref name=\"pevsner\" />\n\nIn the 1840s, the Chapel was turned round to face across fields.  The roof was raised and the interior reconstructed.  The alterations by John Frith were completed in 1848, while the interior has several later additions, including several [[stained glass]] windows.<ref name=\"pevsner\" />  Nine on the ground floor are by [[Henry Holiday]].<ref name=\"chapel\" />\n\nNineteenth-century ministers included [[George Vance Smith]], [[Brooke Herford]], [[Thomas Hinks]] and [[John Edmondson Manning]], who wrote a history of the chapel in 1900.<ref>\"Manning, John Edmondson\", ''[[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]]''</ref>\n\nThe Chapel is linked to '''Channing Hall''', which faces on to [[Surrey Street]].  Designed by [[Flockton and Gibbs]] and completed in 1882, the hall is of [[Italianate architecture|Italianate design]] and is named for [[William Henry Channing]], who served at the Chapel in 1875.<ref name=\"pevsner\" />\n\nThe trustees own many freehold properties in Sheffield.\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.upperchapelsheffield.org.uk/ Official site]\n\n{{Churches in Sheffield}}\n\n[[Category:Churches completed in 1700]]\n[[Category:Churches in Sheffield]]\n[[Category:Grade II listed buildings in Sheffield]]\n[[Category:Grade II listed churches in South Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:Unitarian chapels in England]]\n[[Category:Churches completed in 1848]]\n[[Category:Protestant congregations established in the 17th century]]\n[[Category:1700 establishments in England]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the hamlet in Wales|Upper Chapel, Powys}}\n\n{{Infobox religious building |building_name=Upper Chapel |image=Upper Chapel Sheffield.JPG | caption=Facade of the Upper Chapel | location=[[Sheffield City Centre]]<br>[[South Yorkshire]], [[England]] | map_type=Sheffield\n|geo = {{coord|53.3808|-1.4683|display=inline,title}}\n|religious_affiliation=[[Unitarianism|Unitarian]] |district= |consecration_year= |status= |leadership= |website= |architect= |architecture_type=[[Church (building)|Church]] |architecture_style= |facade_direction= |year_completed=1700 |construction_cost= |capacity= |length= |width= |width_nave= |height_max= |dome_quantity= |dome_height_outer= |dome_height_inner= |dome_dia_outer= |dome_dia_inner= |minaret_quantity= |minaret_height= |spire_quantity= |spire_height= |materials=Brick }}\n\n'''Upper Chapel''' is a [[Unitarianism|Unitarian]] [[chapel]] on Norfolk Street in [[Sheffield City Centre]]. It is a member of the [[General Assembly of Unitarian and Free Christian Churches]], the [[umbrella organisation]] for British Unitarians.<ref>{{Citation | url = http://www.unitarian.org.uk/findcong.shtml?cong=Sheffield%20Norfolk%20Street| title = Find a Congregation: Sheffield| accessdate = 23 January 2011| publisher = The General Assembly of Unitarian and Free Christian Churches (Great Britain)}}</ref> The Chapel is [[Grade II listed]].<ref name=\"chapel\" />\n\nJames Fisher was the vicar at [[Sheffield Parish Church]] during the [[Commonwealth of England]].  He was expelled in the [[Great Ejection]] for refusing to sign the [[Act of Uniformity 1662]], and around a tenth of his parishioners followed him in becoming [[Rational dissenter|Dissenter]]s.<ref name=\"pevsner\">Ruth Harman and John Minnis, ''Pevsner Architectural Guides: Sheffield''</ref>\n\nSeveral splits ensued, but by the 1690s, the dominant group of non-conformists was led by [[Timothy Jollie]].  His congregation constructed Upper Chapel<ref>\"Jollie, Timothy\", ''[[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]]''</ref> as the first [[Nonconformist (Protestantism)|non-conformist]] chapel in Sheffield [[1700 in architecture|in 1700]].<ref name=\"pevsner\" />  It was built of brick and faced on to [[Fargate]].  The chapel originally boasted a congregation of about 1,000 people, a sixth of the city's population.<ref name=\"chapel\">[http://www.upperchapel.org.uk/w/doku.php/uc:history Upper Chapel: History]</ref>  The side walls survive from this period.<ref name=\"pevsner\" />\n\nIn the 1840s, the Chapel was turned round to face across fields.  The roof was raised and the interior reconstructed.  The alterations by John Frith were completed in 1848, while the interior has several later additions, including several [[stained glass]] windows.<ref name=\"pevsner\" />  Nine on the ground floor are by [[Henry Holiday]].<ref name=\"chapel\" />\n\nNineteenth-century ministers included [[George Vance Smith]], [[Brooke Herford]], [[Thomas Hinks]] and [[John Edmondson Manning]], who wrote a history of the chapel in 1900.<ref>\"Manning, John Edmondson\", ''[[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]]''</ref>\n\nThe Chapel is linked to '''Channing Hall''', which faces on to [[Surrey Street]].  Designed by [[Flockton and Gibbs]] and completed in 1882, the hall is of [[Italianate architecture|Italianate design]] and is named for [[William Henry Channing]], who served at the Chapel in 1875.<ref name=\"pevsner\" />\n\nThe trustees own many freehold properties in Sheffield.\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.upperchapel.org.uk/w/doku.php Official site]\n\n{{Churches in Sheffield}}\n\n[[Category:Churches completed in 1700]]\n[[Category:Churches in Sheffield]]\n[[Category:Grade II listed buildings in Sheffield]]\n[[Category:Grade II listed churches in South Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:Unitarian chapels in England]]\n[[Category:Churches completed in 1848]]\n[[Category:Protestant congregations established in the 17th century]]\n[[Category:1700 establishments in England]]\n", "name_user": "Chrisssy", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Upper_Chapel"}
{"title_page": "Belen Jesuit Preparatory School", "text_new": "{{About|the school in Florida|the school in Cuba|Instituto Tecnico Militar}}\n{{Infobox University\n|name              = Belen Jesuit Preparatory School\n|image             = \n|image_size        = 175px\n|caption           =\n|former_name       = Colegio de Bel\u00e9n (1854)\n|motto             = ''Docete Omnes Gentes'' {{small|(Latin)}}\n|mottoeng          = ''Teach All Nations''\n|type              = [[Private school|Private]], [[Roman Catholic]] Non-profit College preparatory [[Single-sex education|All-boys]] Secondary (grades 6\u201312) education institution\n|established       = 1854\n|founder           =  Queen Isabel II of Spain\n|religious_affiliation = [[Roman Catholic]] ([[Society of Jesus|Jesuit]])\n|academic_affiliations = AdvancEd [[Jesuit Schools Network|JSN]] [[Jesuit High School College Counselors Association|JHSCCA]] National Catholic Educational Association\n|president         = Fr.Guillermo Garc\u00eda-Tu\u00f1on, [[Society of Jesus|SJ]]\n|principal         = Jos\u00e9 E. Roca \n|dean              = Mr. Andres De Angulo \n|enrollment        = 1,373 enrollment as of 2020\n|city              = 500 Southwest 127th Avenue [[Miami, Florida|Miami]], [[Miami-Dade County]]\n|state             = [[Florida]] \n|zipcode           = 33184\n|country           = {{USA}}\n|coordinates       = {{coord|25.76304|N|80.40180|W|type:edu_region:US-FL|display=inline,title}}\n|campus            = Urban 33 acres\n|colors            = Blue {{color box|navy}} and {{color box|gold}} Gold\n|athletics         = Varsity team name<br>Belen Wolverines\n|nickname          = Wolverines\n|mascot            = Waldo the Wolverine\n|website           = [http://www.belenjesuit.org belenjesuit.org] \n}}\n'''Belen Jesuit Preparatory School''' is an [[Single-sex education|all-male]], [[Roman Catholic]], [[University-preparatory school|preparatory school]] in [[Miami]], [[Florida]], operated by the [[Society of Jesus]]. It was established in [[Havana]], [[Cuba]], by the [[Society of Jesus|Jesuits]] in 1854, but moved to the [[United States]] after the [[communist]] government of [[Fidel Castro]], himself an [[alumnus]], took power and expelled the Jesuits.<ref>[Ada Evening News February 24, 1961 Ada]</ref> It has since made the [[Cardinal Newman Society]]'s honor roll.<ref>[http://www.chshonor.org/roll/2010/top50.php Honor role]</ref> The name Belen is Spanish for \"Bethlehem.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Google Translation|url=https://translate.google.com/#auto/es/Bethlehem}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===In Cuba===\n<!-- Unsourced image removed: [[Image:1925 - belen.jpg|thumb|right|Colegio de Bel\u00e9n \"The Palace of Education\" (1925-1961)|{{deletable image-caption|1=Sunday, 27 July 2008}}]] -->\nIn 1854, Queen [[Isabella II of Spain]] issued a royal charter founding the \"Colegio de Bel\u00e9n\" in Havana. The school took its name from the building it occupied at its founding, the former convent and convalescent hospital of Our Lady of Belen. Over time, the school expanded through the acquisition of several nearby buildings in Havana. The resulting complex became known as \"El Palacio de Educaci\u00f3n\" (The Palace of Education). \"El Palacio\" now houses the [[Instituto T\u00e9cnico Militar]] (Military Technical Institute).\n\nA meteorological observatory was established in 1857. A facility was built in 1896.<ref name=\"Lanza1904\">{{cite book|author={{Interlanguage link multi|Mariano Guti\u00e9rrez-Lanza|es}}|title=Apuntes historicos acerca del Observatorio del Colegio de Bel\u00e9n, Habana|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=o4EAAAAAMAAJ|year=1904|publisher=Impr. Avisador comercial|location=Havana|language=es}}</ref> The education of students was assigned to the priests and brothers of the Society of Jesus (the Jesuits).\n\n===In the United States===\nIn 1961, the revolutionary regime confiscated the school's property and expelled the Jesuit faculty. The school was re-established in Miami the same year, and began to grow over the next decade. Today, Belen Jesuit sits on a 33-acre site in western Miami-Dade County. There are over 7,000 members of the Belen Alumni Association currently active.\n\nBelen Jesuit is accredited by AdvanceED. The school is also affiliated with the National Catholic Educational Association and is a member of the Jesuit Schools Network and the Jesuit High School College Counselors Association.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.belenjesuit.org/page/about|title=Belen Jesuit Preparatory School|accessdate=December 21, 2018}}</ref> \n\n===Fr. Benito Vi\u00f1es, S.J. Observatory===\nThe Belen Observatory for Astronomy and Meteorology was built with donations from the Belen Jesuit Class of 1972 and is named the Fr. Benito Vi\u00f1es, S.J. Observatory. The observatory has an array of 11 telescopes, and Belen is the only middle/high school in South Florida equipped with a 16\u201d telescope with a charge-coupled device (digital) camera for astrophotography. Weather forecasts from the facility are radioed daily to various cities in Florida. The observatory was grown and made popular under Fr. Pedro Cartaya, S.J.\n\n===The Gian Zumpano Aquatic Center===\nThe Gian Zumpano Aquatic Center was completed on June 6, 2018, and is the home to the Belen Jesuit swimming team. This Olympic size swimming facility was built in honor of Belen alumnus Gian Zumpano form the class of 1986. Gian, was the salutatorian of his class and died at the age of 22. During his time at Belen Jesuit and beyond, he inspired others through his humility and selflessness. The presence of his bust on the pool deck serves as a reminder of his spirit and dedication to teaching young children to swim. The cutting-edge competition complex is an architectural, acoustic and interpretive feat.  It is the first known facility of its kind designed in the Jesuit tradition.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.belenjesuit.org/page/news-detail?pk=956098|title=Belen Jesuit Preparatory School and Zumpano Family to Celebrate Opening of Gian Zumpano Aquatic Center|author=Teresa Martinez|publisher=Belen Jesuit Preparatory School|date=May 21, 2018|accessdate=December 21, 2018}}</ref>  It boasts both a state of the art competition pool and a learn-to-swim pool, used by the over 1,000 area children who attend Belen summer camp every year.\n\n==Financial Assistance==\nBelen Jesuit Preparatory School makes financial assistance available to all students who attend the school regardless of race, color, creed, disability or national origin. The financial assistance program takes the form of hardship assistance. Hardship assistance is determined based on financial need subsequent to the evaluation of the financial assistance application. Belen Jesuit does not award academic or athletic scholarships.\n\nThe Belen financial assistance program is made possible by contributions of friends and family of Belen. The school's three signature events - Annual Gala, Father Izquierdo Memorial Golf Tournament, and the Annual Fr. Dorta- Duque, SJ Memorial Tombola help fund the financial assistance program.\n\n==Academics==\nThe foundation of education at Belen Jesuit is based on religious formation, academic excellence, value education, social responsibility, and athletic achievement. The rigorous curriculum and graduation requirements are designed to ensure all students a chance for admission to the most demanding colleges and universities in the country. Academically, every Belen student has the opportunity to strive for the Magis by participating in a challenging college preparatory curriculum. Additionally, honors courses are offered as early as sixth grade. Advanced placement courses are offered starting in ninth grade, and dual enrollment courses are offered starting in tenth grade. All Belen Jesuit students have the potential to graduate with as many as 13 advanced placement courses (over 20 offered), 10 dual enrollment courses, and 35 honors classes offered in social studies, math, English, science, and Spanish. \n\nBelen Jesuit has been named one of the top U.S. Catholic High Schools by the Newman Society<ref name=\":0\">[http://www.cardinalnewmansociety.org/K-12EDPrograms/CatholicEducationHonorRoll.aspx National Catholic High School Honor Roll] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222081953/http://www.cardinalnewmansociety.org/K-12EDPrograms/CatholicEducationHonorRoll.aspx|date=December 22, 2015}}</ref>and has also been ranked as a top all boys catholic school by Niche.<ref name=\"CHSHR\">[https://www.niche.com/k12/belen-jesuit-prep-school-miami-fl/ Niche]</ref>\n\n==Student life==\nAs a complement to strong academic rigor, student life is enriched by more than 45 scholastic clubs and 47 sports teams. Each student can explore particular interests and choose from an extensive array of options. Belen students have earned local, national and international recognition through their accomplishments in the band program, model United Nations, speech and debate, Mu Alpha Theta, robotics, chess clubs and various other clubs and honor societies. \n\n==The Ignatian Center for the Arts==\nThe Ignatian Center for the Arts, inaugurated in October 2003, is the hub of the Humanities Department. The department includes the following academic areas: art, art history, drama, music, band, speech and debate and philosophy. Facilities include the 665-seat Ophelia & Juan Js. Roca Theater; the Olga & Carlos Saladrigas Art Gallery; the Leopoldo Nu\u00f1ez Rehearsal Hall; seven classrooms and the theater's administrative office. The Saladrigas Gallery displays several professionally curated exhibits, which include an Archdiocesan high school young artists exhibit, a Belen community art show, and numerous other projects.\n\nThe Belen bands program has over 200 student musicians and was established in January 2005. There are three major band units in the school: the jazz band, the concert band and the drum line. The Belen jazz band has won first and second place awards in competitions at Disney World, the Miami-Dade Youth Fair and the Festival of Music in Washington D.C. and Chicago. The bands have three annual concerts at the Roca Theater, while the drum line is a source of \u201cmood and spirit\u201d at pep rallies and athletic competitions. Sections of the bands do charity work during the Christmas season, performing in malls, assisted living facilities, and hospitals.\n\nDrama classes use the Roca Theater for their performances.  Belen presents two high school productions annually and a one production annually from the middle school. Student productions include classics like Death of a Salesman, Fuenteovejuna, One Flew Over the Cuckoo\u2019s Nest, Godspell, A Few Good Men, West Side Story, Sound of Music, Little Shop of Horrors, Beauty and the Beast, The Outsiders, Moon Over Buffalo, Hunchback of Notre Dame and others. The Saladrigas Gallery, which is located adjacent to the theater, hosts both professional and student exhibits throughout the year. \n\n==Athletics==\n{{unreferenced|section|date=November 2018}}\nBelen Jesuit competes in basketball, bowling, crew, cross country, football, golf, lacrosse, soccer, swimming, tennis, track and field, volleyball, water polo, and wrestling. Typically over 900 athletes participate on 47 teams.\n\n==The Ram\u00f3n Guiteras Memorial Library==\nThe Ram\u00f3n Guiteras Memorial Library is located on the campus and serves the student body and faculty of Belen as well as the local community. The library currently lists over 60,000 volumes, 95,000 ebooks, and dozens of subscriptions to electronic databases. The library staff includes one professional librarian and four assistants.<ref name=\"BJPS-l\">[https://www.belenjesuit.org/page/student-life/library Belen Jesuit Preparatory School - Library] Retrieved December 21, 2018.</ref> \n\nThe library houses La Colecci\u00f3n Cubana (The Cuban Collection), a special collection of Cuban books. La Colecci\u00f3n Cubana consists of over 8,000 volumes, written either on the subject of Cuba or penned by Cubans and Cuban-Americans. La Colecci\u00f3n Cubana is open to the public and is the second-largest collection of Cuban books and other media outside of Cuba<ref name=\"BJPS-l\"/>\n\n==Notable alumni==\n{{Main|List of Belen Jesuit Preparatory School people}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book|title=Album conmemorativo del quincuagesimo aniversario de la fundaci\u00f3n en la Habana del Colegio de Bel\u00e9n de la Compa\u00f1ia de Jesus|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AWBGAAAAYAAJ|year=1904|publisher=Impr. Avisador comercial|location=Havana|language=es}}\n*{{cite book|title=Handbook of Learned Societies and Institutions: America|year=1908|publisher=[[Carnegie Institution of Washington]]|location=USA|via=[[HathiTrust]]|chapter=Cuba: Colegio de Bel\u00e9n|chapterurl=http://hdl.handle.net/2027/uc2.ark:/13960/t5t72q98c?urlappend=%3Bseq=492}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscategory|Colegio de Bel\u00e9n}}\n*[http://www.belenjesuit.org Belen Jesuit Home Page]\n\n\n{{-}}\n{{Jesuit Secondary Education Association}}\n{{Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Miami |state=collapsed}}\u2009\n{{Boys' schools in Florida}}\n[[Category:Boys' schools in the United States]]\n[[Category:Education in Miami]]\n[[Category:Jesuit high schools in the United States]]\n[[Category:Private schools in Miami-Dade County, Florida]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Miami]]\n[[Category:Catholic secondary schools in Florida]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1854]]\n[[Category:High schools in Miami-Dade County]]\n[[Category:Private middle schools in Florida]]\n[[Category:Schools with a Royal Charter]]\n[[C[[Category:Religious buildings and structures in Havana]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic churches in Havana]]\n[[Category:18th-century Roman Catholic church buildings]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Havana]]\n[[Category:Neoclassical architecture in Cuba]]ategory:1961 establishments in Florida]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the school in Florida|the school in Cuba|Instituto Tecnico Militar}}\n{{Infobox University\n|name              = Belen Jesuit Preparatory School\n|image             = \n|image_size        = 175px\n|caption           =\n|former_name       = Colegio de Bel\u00e9n (1854)\n|motto             = ''Docete Omnes Gentes'' {{small|(Latin)}}\n|mottoeng          = ''Teach All Nations''\n|type              = [[Private school|Private]], [[Roman Catholic]] Non-profit College preparatory [[Single-sex education|All-boys]] Secondary (grades 6\u201312) education institution\n|established       = 1854\n|founder           =  Queen Isabel II of Spain\n|religious_affiliation = [[Roman Catholic]] ([[Society of Jesus|Jesuit]])\n|academic_affiliations = AdvancEd [[Jesuit Schools Network|JSN]] [[Jesuit High School College Counselors Association|JHSCCA]] National Catholic Educational Association\n|president         = Fr.Guillermo Garc\u00eda-Tu\u00f1on, [[Society of Jesus|SJ]]\n|principal         = Jos\u00e9 E. Roca \n|dean              = Mr. Andres De Angulo \n|enrollment        = 1,378 enrollment_as 2019\n|city              = 500 Southwest 127th Avenue [[Miami, Florida|Miami]], [[Miami-Dade County]]\n|state             = [[Florida]] \n|zipcode           = 33184\n|country           = {{USA}}\n|coordinates       = {{coord|25.76304|N|80.40180|W|type:edu_region:US-FL|display=inline,title}}\n|campus            = Urban 33 acres\n|colors            = Blue {{color box|navy}} and {{color box|gold}} Gold\n|athletics         = Varsity team name<br>Belen Wolverines\n|nickname          = Wolverines\n|mascot            = Waldo the Wolverine\n|website           = [http://www.belenjesuit.org belenjesuit.org] \n}}\n'''Belen Jesuit Preparatory School''' is an [[Single-sex education|all-male]], [[Roman Catholic]], [[University-preparatory school|preparatory school]] in [[Miami]], [[Florida]], operated by the [[Society of Jesus]]. It was established in [[Havana]], [[Cuba]], by the [[Society of Jesus|Jesuits]] in 1854, but moved to the [[United States]] after the [[communist]] government of [[Fidel Castro]], himself an [[alumnus]], took power and expelled the Jesuits.<ref>[Ada Evening News February 24, 1961 Ada]</ref> It has since made the [[Cardinal Newman Society]]'s honor roll.<ref>[http://www.chshonor.org/roll/2010/top50.php Honor role]</ref> The name Belen is Spanish for \"Bethlehem.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Google Translation|url=https://translate.google.com/#auto/es/Bethlehem}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===In Cuba===\n<!-- Unsourced image removed: [[Image:1925 - belen.jpg|thumb|right|Colegio de Bel\u00e9n \"The Palace of Education\" (1925-1961)|{{deletable image-caption|1=Sunday, 27 July 2008}}]] -->\nIn 1854, Queen [[Isabella II of Spain]] issued a royal charter founding the \"Colegio de Bel\u00e9n\" in Havana. The school took its name from the building it occupied at its founding, the former convent and convalescent hospital of Our Lady of Belen. Over time, the school expanded through the acquisition of several nearby buildings in Havana. The resulting complex became known as \"El Palacio de Educaci\u00f3n\" (The Palace of Education). \"El Palacio\" now houses the [[Instituto T\u00e9cnico Militar]] (Military Technical Institute).\n\nA meteorological observatory was established in 1857. A facility was built in 1896.<ref name=\"Lanza1904\">{{cite book|author={{Interlanguage link multi|Mariano Guti\u00e9rrez-Lanza|es}}|title=Apuntes historicos acerca del Observatorio del Colegio de Bel\u00e9n, Habana|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=o4EAAAAAMAAJ|year=1904|publisher=Impr. Avisador comercial|location=Havana|language=es}}</ref> The education of students was assigned to the priests and brothers of the Society of Jesus (the Jesuits).\n\n===In the United States===\nIn 1961, the revolutionary regime confiscated the school's property and expelled the Jesuit faculty. The school was re-established in Miami the same year, and began to grow over the next decade. Today, Belen Jesuit sits on a 33-acre site in western Miami-Dade County. There are over 7,000 members of the Belen Alumni Association currently active.\n\nBelen Jesuit is accredited by AdvanceED. The school is also affiliated with the National Catholic Educational Association and is a member of the Jesuit Schools Network and the Jesuit High School College Counselors Association.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.belenjesuit.org/page/about|title=Belen Jesuit Preparatory School|accessdate=December 21, 2018}}</ref> \n\n===Fr. Benito Vi\u00f1es, S.J. Observatory===\nThe Belen Observatory for Astronomy and Meteorology was built with donations from the Belen Jesuit Class of 1972 and is named the Fr. Benito Vi\u00f1es, S.J. Observatory. The observatory has an array of 11 telescopes, and Belen is the only middle/high school in South Florida equipped with a 16\u201d telescope with a charge-coupled device (digital) camera for astrophotography. Weather forecasts from the facility are radioed daily to various cities in Florida. The observatory was grown and made popular under Fr. Pedro Cartaya, S.J.\n\n===The Gian Zumpano Aquatic Center===\nThe Gian Zumpano Aquatic Center was completed on June 6, 2018, and is the home to the Belen Jesuit swimming team. This Olympic size swimming facility was built in honor of Belen alumnus Gian Zumpano form the class of 1986. Gian, was the salutatorian of his class and died at the age of 22. During his time at Belen Jesuit and beyond, he inspired others through his humility and selflessness. The presence of his bust on the pool deck serves as a reminder of his spirit and dedication to teaching young children to swim. The cutting-edge competition complex is an architectural, acoustic and interpretive feat.  It is the first known facility of its kind designed in the Jesuit tradition.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.belenjesuit.org/page/news-detail?pk=956098|title=Belen Jesuit Preparatory School and Zumpano Family to Celebrate Opening of Gian Zumpano Aquatic Center|author=Teresa Martinez|publisher=Belen Jesuit Preparatory School|date=May 21, 2018|accessdate=December 21, 2018}}</ref>  It boasts both a state of the art competition pool and a learn-to-swim pool, used by the over 1,000 area children who attend Belen summer camp every year.\n\n==Financial Assistance==\nBelen Jesuit Preparatory School makes financial assistance available to all students who attend the school regardless of race, color, creed, disability or national origin. The financial assistance program takes the form of hardship assistance. Hardship assistance is determined based on financial need subsequent to the evaluation of the financial assistance application. Belen Jesuit does not award academic or athletic scholarships.\n\nThe Belen financial assistance program is made possible by contributions of friends and family of Belen. The school's three signature events - Annual Gala, Father Izquierdo Memorial Golf Tournament, and the Annual Fr. Dorta- Duque, SJ Memorial Tombola help fund the financial assistance program.\n\n==Academics==\nThe foundation of education at Belen Jesuit is based on religious formation, academic excellence, value education, social responsibility, and athletic achievement. The rigorous curriculum and graduation requirements are designed to ensure all students a chance for admission to the most demanding colleges and universities in the country. Academically, every Belen student has the opportunity to strive for the Magis by participating in a challenging college preparatory curriculum. Additionally, honors courses are offered as early as sixth grade. Advanced placement courses are offered starting in ninth grade, and dual enrollment courses are offered starting in tenth grade. All Belen Jesuit students have the potential to graduate with as many as 13 advanced placement courses (over 20 offered), 10 dual enrollment courses, and 35 honors classes offered in social studies, math, English, science, and Spanish. \n\nBelen Jesuit has been named one of the top U.S. Catholic High Schools by the Newman Society<ref name=\":0\">[http://www.cardinalnewmansociety.org/K-12EDPrograms/CatholicEducationHonorRoll.aspx National Catholic High School Honor Roll] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222081953/http://www.cardinalnewmansociety.org/K-12EDPrograms/CatholicEducationHonorRoll.aspx|date=December 22, 2015}}</ref>and has also been ranked as a top all boys catholic school by Niche.<ref name=\"CHSHR\">[https://www.niche.com/k12/belen-jesuit-prep-school-miami-fl/ Niche]</ref>\n\n==Student life==\nAs a complement to strong academic rigor, student life is enriched by more than 45 scholastic clubs and 47 sports teams. Each student can explore particular interests and choose from an extensive array of options. Belen students have earned local, national and international recognition through their accomplishments in the band program, model United Nations, speech and debate, Mu Alpha Theta, robotics, chess clubs and various other clubs and honor societies. \n\n==The Ignatian Center for the Arts==\nThe Ignatian Center for the Arts, inaugurated in October 2003, is the hub of the Humanities Department. The department includes the following academic areas: art, art history, drama, music, band, speech and debate and philosophy. Facilities include the 665-seat Ophelia & Juan Js. Roca Theater; the Olga & Carlos Saladrigas Art Gallery; the Leopoldo Nu\u00f1ez Rehearsal Hall; seven classrooms and the theater's administrative office. The Saladrigas Gallery displays several professionally curated exhibits, which include an Archdiocesan high school young artists exhibit, a Belen community art show, and numerous other projects.\n\nThe Belen bands program has over 200 student musicians and was established in January 2005. There are three major band units in the school: the jazz band, the concert band and the drum line. The Belen jazz band has won first and second place awards in competitions at Disney World, the Miami-Dade Youth Fair and the Festival of Music in Washington D.C. and Chicago. The bands have three annual concerts at the Roca Theater, while the drum line is a source of \u201cmood and spirit\u201d at pep rallies and athletic competitions. Sections of the bands do charity work during the Christmas season, performing in malls, assisted living facilities, and hospitals.\n\nDrama classes use the Roca Theater for their performances.  Belen presents two high school productions annually and a one production annually from the middle school. Student productions include classics like Death of a Salesman, Fuenteovejuna, One Flew Over the Cuckoo\u2019s Nest, Godspell, A Few Good Men, West Side Story, Sound of Music, Little Shop of Horrors, Beauty and the Beast, The Outsiders, Moon Over Buffalo, Hunchback of Notre Dame and others. The Saladrigas Gallery, which is located adjacent to the theater, hosts both professional and student exhibits throughout the year. \n\n==Athletics==\n{{unreferenced|section|date=November 2018}}\nBelen Jesuit competes in basketball, bowling, crew, cross country, football, golf, lacrosse, soccer, swimming, tennis, track and field, volleyball, water polo, and wrestling. Typically over 900 athletes participate on 47 teams.\n\n==The Ram\u00f3n Guiteras Memorial Library==\nThe Ram\u00f3n Guiteras Memorial Library is located on the campus and serves the student body and faculty of Belen as well as the local community. The library currently lists over 60,000 volumes, 95,000 ebooks, and dozens of subscriptions to electronic databases. The library staff includes one professional librarian and four assistants.<ref name=\"BJPS-l\">[https://www.belenjesuit.org/page/student-life/library Belen Jesuit Preparatory School - Library] Retrieved December 21, 2018.</ref> \n\nThe library houses La Colecci\u00f3n Cubana (The Cuban Collection), a special collection of Cuban books. La Colecci\u00f3n Cubana consists of over 8,000 volumes, written either on the subject of Cuba or penned by Cubans and Cuban-Americans. La Colecci\u00f3n Cubana is open to the public and is the second-largest collection of Cuban books and other media outside of Cuba<ref name=\"BJPS-l\"/>\n\n==Notable alumni==\n{{Main|List of Belen Jesuit Preparatory School people}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book|title=Album conmemorativo del quincuagesimo aniversario de la fundaci\u00f3n en la Habana del Colegio de Bel\u00e9n de la Compa\u00f1ia de Jesus|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AWBGAAAAYAAJ|year=1904|publisher=Impr. Avisador comercial|location=Havana|language=es}}\n*{{cite book|title=Handbook of Learned Societies and Institutions: America|year=1908|publisher=[[Carnegie Institution of Washington]]|location=USA|via=[[HathiTrust]]|chapter=Cuba: Colegio de Bel\u00e9n|chapterurl=http://hdl.handle.net/2027/uc2.ark:/13960/t5t72q98c?urlappend=%3Bseq=492}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscategory|Colegio de Bel\u00e9n}}\n*[http://www.belenjesuit.org Belen Jesuit Home Page]\n\n\n{{-}}\n{{Jesuit Secondary Education Association}}\n{{Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Miami |state=collapsed}}\u2009\n{{Boys' schools in Florida}}\n[[Category:Boys' schools in the United States]]\n[[Category:Education in Miami]]\n[[Category:Jesuit high schools in the United States]]\n[[Category:Private schools in Miami-Dade County, Florida]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Miami]]\n[[Category:Catholic secondary schools in Florida]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1854]]\n[[Category:High schools in Miami-Dade County]]\n[[Category:Private middle schools in Florida]]\n[[Category:Schools with a Royal Charter]]\n[[C[[Category:Religious buildings and structures in Havana]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic churches in Havana]]\n[[Category:18th-century Roman Catholic church buildings]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Havana]]\n[[Category:Neoclassical architecture in Cuba]]ategory:1961 establishments in Florida]]\n", "name_user": "Gerbivore", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Belen_Jesuit_Preparatory_School"}
{"title_page": "Zigrasite", "text_new": "{{Infobox mineral\n| name          = Zigrasite\n| category      = [[Phosphate minerals]]\n| image         =\n| imagesize     = 360\n| formula       = MgZr(PO<sub>4</sub>)<sub>2</sub>(H<sub>2</sub>O)<sub>4</sub>\n| strunz        = 8.CE.75\n| dana          = 40.1.5.2\n| symmetry      = P{{overline|1}}\n| unit cell     = a = 5.3049(2) \u00c5, b = 9.3372(4) \u00c5, c = 9.6282(4) \u00c5\n\u03b1 = 97.348(1)\u00b0, \u03b2 = 91.534(1)\u00b0, \u03b3 = 90.512(1)\u00b0\n| color         = Off-white to pale yellow or light tan\n| habit         = Subhedral blocky\n| system        = [[Trigonal crystal system|Triclinic]]\n| class         = {{overline|1}} - Pinacoidal\n| cleavage      = Imperfect cleavage in two directions, parallel to (010) and (001)\n| fracture      = Hackly\n| tenacity      = Brittle\n| mohs          = 3\n| luster        = Vitreous\n| streak        = white\n| diaphaneity   = Opaque\n| gravity       = 2.76\n| density       = 2.76-2.66\n| opticalprop   = Uniaxial (\u2212)\n| refractive    = \u03b1 1.597(1), \u03b2 1.622 (1), \u03b3 1.635 (1) \n| references    = <ref name=Haw>F. C. Hawthorne, N. A. Ball, J. W. Nizamoff, W. B. Simmons; Zigrasite, MgZr(PO4)2(H2O)4, a new phosphate mineral from the Dunton Quarry, Newry, Oxford County, Maine, USA. Mineralogical Magazine ; 73 (3): 415\u2013420. doi: https://doi.org/10.1180/minmag.2009.073.3.415</ref><ref name=Hawt>Hawthorne, F., & Simmons, W. (2010). The crystal structure of zigrasite, MgZr(PO4)2(H2O)4, a heteropolyhedral framework structure. Mineralogical Magazine, 74(3), 567-575. doi:10.1180/minmag.2010.074.3.567\n</ref>\n}}\n'''Zigrasite''' is a [[Phosphate minerals|phosphate mineral]] with the chemical formula of MgZr(PO<sub>4</sub>)<sub>2</sub>(H<sub>2</sub>O)<sub>4</sub>. Zigrasite was discovered and is only known to occur in the [https://www.mindat.org/loc-3780.html Dunton Quarry] at [[Oxford County, Maine]]. Zigrasite was specifically found in the giant 1972 gem tourmaline-bearing pocket at the Dunton Quarry. Zigrasite is named after [http://www.jameszigras.com/about.html James Zigras] who originally discovered and brought the mineral to attention.\n\n==Occurrence==\nZigrasite is found in association with [[tourmaline]], [[microcline]], [[quartz]], [[albite]], [[beryl]], [[amblygonite]]-[[montebrasite]], [[childrenite]]-[[eosphorite]], and [[apatite]]. It is crystallized as one of the last minerals during pocket formation. The crystals themselves were found perched on a crystal of tourmaline from the giant 1972 pocket at the [https://www.mindat.org/loc-3780.html Dunton Quarry.] The quarry itself is located in a complex rare-element granitic [[pegmatite]] that has produced large quantities of gem tourmaline as well as many other rare phosphate species.<ref name=Haw />\n\n==Physical Properties==\nZigrasite is an offwhite to pale yellow or light tan in color. Zigrasite exhibits a vitreous luster, and a white streak. The Mohs hardness is 3.The measured( Berman Balance) and calculated densities are 2.76(4) and 2.66 g/cm3 respectively. Zigrasite exhibits imperfect cleavage in two directions, parallel to (010) and (001), it shows no parting, is brittle and has hackly fracture. In transmitted light zigrasite is colorless and non-pleochroic, biaxial negative with indices of refraction \u03b1 1.597(1) \u03b2 1.622 (1), \u03b3 1.635 (1). Zigrasite is translucent and shows a light blue to pale yellow [[cathodoluminescence]].<ref name=Haw />\n\n== Crystal Structure==\n\nZigrasite's atomic coordination consists of two phosphorus sites which are solely occupied by phosphorus and tetrahedrally coordinated by four oxygen anions with <P-O> distances of 1.532 and 1.533 \u00c5. There are also two magnesium, both of which are occupied solely by Mg and are octahedrally coordinated by two oxygen anions and four (H<sub>2</sub>O) groups with <Mg-O> distances of 2.064 and 2.075 \u00c5. There is a single zircon site solely occupied by zircon and octahedrally coorinated by six oxygen anions with a <Zr-O> distance of 2.065 \u00c5.\n\nThe zircon octahedron shares corners with six (PO<sub>4</sub>) tetrehedra to form a pinwheel cluster. This cluster forms a fragment of a Zr(PO<sub>4</sub>)<sub>2</sub> sheet which is parallel to the (001) direction. Alternating tetrahedra point up and down relative to the plane of the sheet. Isolated Mg(H<sub>2</sub>O)6) octahedrea are arranged in layers parallel to (001). These layers are intercalated between the [Zr(PO<sub>4</sub>)<sub>2</sub>] sheets linking through the apical vertices of the (PO<sub>4</sub>) tetrahedra. This structure is formally a heteropolyhedral framework with linkage weaker in the c direction accounting for cleavage.<ref name=Hawt/>\n\n== Chemical Properties ==\nZigrasite is one of 3 compositional variations in zircon phosphate grains from the giant 1972 tourmaline pocket, representing the magnesium phase with [[Mahlmoodite|malhmoodite]] representing the iron phase and an as of yet unnamed calcium-analogue. Zigrasite can be considered to be the magnesium end member for the zircon phosphate grains found in the giant 1972 pocket.<ref name=Haw /> Zigrasite exhibits hydrogen bonding which increases linkage within the layer of magnesium octahedra.<ref name=Hawt/>\n\n== Chemical Composition ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Oxide\n!wt%\n|-\n|P<sub>2</sub>O<sub>5</sub>\n|37.59\n|-\n|ZrO<sub>2</sub>\n|32.27\n|-\n|HfO<sub>2</sub>\n|0.34\n|-\n|FeO\n|0.20\n|-\n|MgO\n|10.37\n|-\n|ZnO\n|0.17\n|-\n|F\n|0.13\n|-\n|LOI\n|18.60\n|-\n|Sub Total\n|99.67\n|-\n|Less O\u039eF<sub>2</sub>\n|0.05\n|-\n|Total\n|99.62\n|}\n\n== X-ray crystallography ==\nThe powder-diffraction pattern was recorded with  Cu-Ka X-radiation on a DebyeScherrer camera with a diameter of114.6&nbsp;mm and a Gandolfi attachment. Refinement of the unit-cell parameters gave the following values: a = 5.321(7) \u00c5 , b = 9.360(10) \u00c5 , c = 9.660(8)\u00c5  , a = 97.38(10)\u00ba, b = 91.29(9)\u00ba, g = 90.58(9)\u00ba, V = 477.0(5) \u00c5 3 . Unit-cell dimensions were also determined on a Bruker single-crystal diffractometer using graphite-monochromated Mo-Ka Xradiation and the resulting values (a = 5.3049(2) \u00c5 , b = 9.3372(4) \u00c5, c = 9.6282(5) \u00c5, a = 97.348(1)\u00ba, b = 91.534(1)\u00ba, g = 90.512(4)\u00ba) are in close agreement with those determined by powder diffraction.<ref name=Hawt/>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Intensity\n!d-spacing\n!hkl\n\n|-\n|100\n|9.550\n|001\n|-\n|10\n|7.489\n|002\n|-\n|40\n|4.589\n|110\n|-\n|50\n|4.411\n|0{{overline|2}}1\n|-\n|70\n|4.108\n|{{overline|1}}11\n|-\n|50\n|4.008\n|111\n|-\n|30\n|3.569\n|0{{overline|2}}2\n|-\n|20\n|3.273\n|{{overline|1}}12\n|-\n|40\n|3.177\n|112\n|-\n|10\n|2.805\n|0{{overline|2}}3\n|-\n|10\n|2.688\n|{{overline|1}}30\n|-\n|30b\n|2.660\n|200\n|-\n|10b\n|2.198\n|0{{overline|4}}2\n|-\n|10\n|2.052\n|{{overline|2}}22\n|-\n|10b\n|2.006\n|222\n|}\n\n==See also==\n[[List of minerals|List of Minerals<br />]][[List of minerals named after people]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.mindat.org/loc-3780.html Dunton Quarry]\n*[http://www.jameszigras.com/about.html James Zigras]\n\n<br />\n\n[[Category:Phosphate minerals]]\n[[Category:Zirconium minerals]]\n[[Category:Triclinic minerals]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox mineral\n| name          = Zigrasite\n| category      = [[Phosphate minerals]]\n| image         =\n| imagesize     = 360\n| formula       = MgZr(PO<sub>4</sub>)<sub>2</sub>(H<sub>2</sub>O)<sub>4</sub>\n| strunz        = 8.CE.75\n| dana          = 40.1.5.2\n| symmetry      = P{{overline|1}}\n| unit cell     = a = 5.3049(2) \u00c5, b = 9.3372(4) \u00c5, c = 9.6282(4) \u00c5\n\u03b1 = 97.348(1)\u00b0, \u03b2 = 91.534(1)\u00b0, \u03b3 = 90.512(1)\u00b0\n| color         = Off-white to pale yellow or light tan\n| habit         = Subhedral blocky\n| system        = [[Trigonal crystal system|Triclinic]]\n| class         = {{overline|1}} - Pinacoidal\n| cleavage      = Imperfect cleavage in two directions, parallel to (010) and (001)\n| fracture      = Hackly\n| tenacity      = Brittle\n| mohs          = 3\n| luster        = Vitreous\n| streak        = white\n| diaphaneity   = Opaque\n| gravity       = 2.76\n| density       = 2.76-2.66\n| opticalprop   = Uniaxial (\u2212)\n| refractive    = \u03b1 1.597(1), \u03b2 1.622 (1), \u03b3 1.635 (1) \n| references    = <ref name=Haw>F. C. Hawthorne, N. A. Ball, J. W. Nizamoff, W. B. Simmons; Zigrasite, MgZr(PO4)2(H2O)4, a new phosphate mineral from the Dunton Quarry, Newry, Oxford County, Maine, USA. Mineralogical Magazine ; 73 (3): 415\u2013420. doi: https://doi.org/10.1180/minmag.2009.073.3.415</ref><ref name=Hawt>Hawthorne, F., & Simmons, W. (2010). The crystal structure of zigrasite, MgZr(PO4)2(H2O)4, a heteropolyhedral framework structure. Mineralogical Magazine, 74(3), 567-575. doi:10.1180/minmag.2010.074.3.567\n</ref>\n}}\n'''Zigrasite''' is a [[Phosphate minerals|phosphate mineral]] with the chemical formula of MgZr(PO<sub>4</sub>)<sub>2</sub>(H<sub>2</sub>O)<sub>4</sub>. Zigrasite was discovered and is only known to occur in the [https://www.mindat.org/loc-3780.html Dunton Quarry] at [[Oxford County, Maine]]. Zigrasite was specifically found in the giant 1972 gem tourmaline-bearing pocket at the Dunton Quarry. Zigrasite is named after [http://www.jameszigras.com/about.html James Zigras] who originally discovered and brought the mineral to attention.\n\n==Occurrence==\nZigrasite is found in association with [[tourmaline]], [[microcline]], [[quartz]], [[albite]], [[beryl]], [[amblygonite]]-[[montebrasite]], [[childrenite]]-[[eosphorite]], and [[apatite]]. It is crystallized as one of the last minerals during pocket formation. The crystals themselves were found perched on a crystal of tourmaline from the giant 1972 pocket at the [https://www.mindat.org/loc-3780.html Dunton Quarry.] The quarry itself is located in a complex rare-element granitic [[pegmatite]] that has produced large quantities of gem tourmaline as well as many other rare phosphate species.<ref name=Haw />\n\n==Physical Properties==\nZigrasite is an offwhite to pale yellow or light tan in color. Zigrasite exhibits a vitreous luster, and a white streak. The Mohs hardness is 3.The measured( Berman Balance) and calculated densities are 2.76(4) and 2.66 g/cm3 respectively. Zigrasite exhibits imperfect cleavage in two directions, parrallel to (010) and (001), it shows no parting, is brittle and has hackly fracture. In transmitted light zigrasite is colorless and non-pleochroic, biaxial negative with indices of refraction \u03b1 1.597(1) \u03b2 1.622 (1), \u03b3 1.635 (1). Zigrasite is translucent and shows a light blue to pale yellow [[cathodoluminescence]].<ref name=Haw />\n\n== Crystal Structure==\n\nZigrasite's atomic coordination consists of two phosphorus sites which are solely occupied by phosphorus and tetrahedrally coordinated by four oxygen anions with <P-O> distances of 1.532 and 1.533 \u00c5. There are also two magnesium, both of which are occupied solely by Mg and are octahedrally coordinated by two oxygen anions and four (H<sub>2</sub>O) groups with <Mg-O> distances of 2.064 and 2.075 \u00c5. There is a single zircon site solely occupied by zircon and octahedrally coorinated by six oxygen anions with a <Zr-O> distance of 2.065 \u00c5.\n\nThe zircon octahedron shares corners with six (PO<sub>4</sub>) tetrehedra to form a pinwheel cluster. This cluster forms a fragment of a Zr(PO<sub>4</sub>)<sub>2</sub> sheet which is parallel to the (001) direction. Alternating tetrahedra point up and down relative to the plane of the sheet. Isolated Mg(H<sub>2</sub>O)6) octahedrea are arranged in layers parallel to (001). These layers are intercalated between the [Zr(PO<sub>4</sub>)<sub>2</sub>] sheets linking through the apical vertices of the (PO<sub>4</sub>) tetrahedra. This structure is formally a heteropolyhedral framework with linkage weaker in the c direction accounting for cleavage.<ref name=Hawt/>\n\n== Chemical Properties ==\nZigrasite is one of 3 compositional variations in zircon phosphate grains from the giant 1972 tourmaline pocket, representing the magnesium phase with [[Mahlmoodite|malhmoodite]] representing the iron phase and an as of yet unnamed calcium-analogue. Zigrasite can be considered to be the magnesium end member for the zircon phosphate grains found in the giant 1972 pocket.<ref name=Haw /> Zigrasite exhibits hydrogen bonding which increases linkage within the layer of magnesium octahedra.<ref name=Hawt/>\n\n== Chemical Composition ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Oxide\n!wt%\n|-\n|P<sub>2</sub>O<sub>5</sub>\n|37.59\n|-\n|ZrO<sub>2</sub>\n|32.27\n|-\n|HfO<sub>2</sub>\n|0.34\n|-\n|FeO\n|0.20\n|-\n|MgO\n|10.37\n|-\n|ZnO\n|0.17\n|-\n|F\n|0.13\n|-\n|LOI\n|18.60\n|-\n|Sub Total\n|99.67\n|-\n|Less O\u039eF<sub>2</sub>\n|0.05\n|-\n|Total\n|99.62\n|}\n\n== X-ray crystallography ==\nThe powder-diffraction pattern was recorded with  Cu-Ka X-radiation on a DebyeScherrer camera with a diameter of114.6&nbsp;mm and a Gandolfi attachment. Refinement of the unit-cell parameters gave the following values: a = 5.321(7) \u00c5 , b = 9.360(10) \u00c5 , c = 9.660(8)\u00c5  , a = 97.38(10)\u00ba, b = 91.29(9)\u00ba, g = 90.58(9)\u00ba, V = 477.0(5) \u00c5 3 . Unit-cell dimensions were also determined on a Bruker single-crystal diffractometer using graphite-monochromated Mo-Ka Xradiation and the resulting values (a = 5.3049(2) \u00c5 , b = 9.3372(4) \u00c5, c = 9.6282(5) \u00c5, a = 97.348(1)\u00ba, b = 91.534(1)\u00ba, g = 90.512(4)\u00ba) are in close agreement with those determined by powder diffraction.<ref name=Hawt/>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Intensity\n!d-spacing\n!hkl\n\n|-\n|100\n|9.550\n|001\n|-\n|10\n|7.489\n|002\n|-\n|40\n|4.589\n|110\n|-\n|50\n|4.411\n|0{{overline|2}}1\n|-\n|70\n|4.108\n|{{overline|1}}11\n|-\n|50\n|4.008\n|111\n|-\n|30\n|3.569\n|0{{overline|2}}2\n|-\n|20\n|3.273\n|{{overline|1}}12\n|-\n|40\n|3.177\n|112\n|-\n|10\n|2.805\n|0{{overline|2}}3\n|