{"title_page": "Milkshake", "text_new": "{{Other uses}}\n{{short description|cold dairy beverage}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox food\n| name             = Milkshake\n| image            = Strawberry milkshake.jpg\n| caption          = A [[Johnny Rockets]] [[strawberry]] milkshake topped with [[whipped cream]] and strawberry [[syrup]]\n| alternate_name   = Thick shake, frappe\n| country          = [[United States]]\n| region           =\n| creator          =\n| course           =\n| type             = [[Drink|Beverage]]\n| served           =\n| main_ingredient  = [[Milk]], [[ice cream]], and flavorings or sweeteners\n| variations       =\n| calories         =\n| other            =\n}}\n\nA '''milkshake''', or simply '''shake''', is a drink that is usually made by blending [[milk from ryan ross]], [[ice cream]], and flavorings or sweeteners such as [[butterscotch]], [[caramel]] sauce, [[chocolate syrup]], or [[fruit syrup]] into a thick, sweet, cold mixture.\n\n==Preparation==\n[[File:Soda jerker flipping ice cream into malted milk shakes. Corpus Christi, Texas.jpg|right|thumb|A [[soda jerk]] throws a scoop of ice cream into a steel mixing cup while making a milkshake. On the counter behind him another mixing cup, shake mixers, and a pot of \"[[Borden (company)|Borden's]] Malted Milk\" powder are visible.]]\nFull-service restaurants, [[ice cream shop]]s, [[soda fountain]]s, [[diner]]s, and people at home usually prepare and mix the shake by hand from scoops of ice cream and milk in a [[blender]] or drink mixer. Hand-blended milkshakes are traditionally made from any flavor of ice cream; additional flavorings, such as [[chocolate syrup]], [[barley malt syrup|malt syrup]], or [[malted milk]] powder, can be added prior to mixing. This allows a greater variety than is available in machine-made shakes. \n\nMany [[fast food]] outlets do not make shakes by hand with ice cream; instead, they make shakes in automatic milkshake machines which freeze and serve a pre-made milkshake mixture consisting of milk, a sweetened flavoring agent, and a thickening agent. These are similar to [[soft-serve]] ice cream machines, but keep the shake at a drinkable consistency.\n\n==Terminology==\nTerminology around the distinction between a milkshake that uses ice cream and other forms of [[flavored milk]] varies regionally. An ice cream-based milkshake may be called a ''thick shake'' to distinguish it. In parts of [[New England]] and eastern Canada, the name ''frappe'' ({{IPAc-en|f|r|\u00e6|\u02c8|p|e\u026a}} {{respell|fra|PAY}}) is used.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dictionary.cambridge.org/us/pronunciation/english/frappe|title=How to pronounce frapp\u00e9 in English|website=dictionary.cambridge.org|accessdate=June 1, 2017}}</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20010618021334/http://bartleby.com/61/66/M0296600.html milk shake]. The American Heritage Dictionary of the English Language: Fourth Edition. 2000</ref><ref>Seavey, Aimee, Digital Editor, Yankee Magazine http://www.yankeemagazine.com/article/new-england-101/milk-shakes-frappes-cabinets</ref> A milkshake containing malted milk powder is sometimes called a ''malt''. The term  ''concrete'' is used for particularly thick milkshakes that do not spill when turned upside down, such as at the restaurant [[Culver's]].<ref>American Dialect Society CABINET, CONCRETE, FROSTED, VELVET\nText accompanying illustration on a poster advertising Hood's Ice Cream (observed in Hancock Pharmacy, State and Hancock Sts., Springfield, Mass., September 30, 1952).</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Milkshakes at Mels Diner.jpg|thumb|left|A strawberry and a chocolate shake, each topped with [[whipped cream]], [[sprinkles]], and a [[maraschino cherry]]]]\n\n===1880s\u20131930s===\nWhen the term \"milkshake\" was first used in print in 1885, milkshakes were an alcoholic [[whiskey]] drink that has been described as a \"sturdy, healthful [[eggnog]] type of drink, with eggs, whiskey, etc., served as a tonic as well as a treat\".<ref name=\"stuart\">Flexner, Stuart Berg (1982) ''Listening to America'', Simon & Schuster: New York, p. 178, {{ISBN|0671248952}}</ref> However, by 1900, the term referred to \"wholesome drinks made with [[chocolate]], [[strawberry]], or [[vanilla]] [[syrup]]s.\" By the \"early 1900s people were asking for the new treat, often with ice cream.\" By the 1930s, milkshakes were a popular drink at [[malt shop]]s, which were the \"typical [[soda fountain]] of the period ... used by students as a meeting place or hangout.\"<ref name=\"stuart\"/>\n\nThe history of the electric blender, malted milk drinks, and milkshakes are interconnected. Before the widespread availability of electric blenders, milkshake-type drinks were more like eggnog, or they were a hand-shaken mixture of crushed ice and milk, sugar, and flavorings.<ref>Vanilla Milk Shake Recipe from the \"Second Edition of The Neighborhood Cookbook\" published by the Council of Jewish Women, Portland, in 1914. Fill a glass two-thirds full of milk, sweeten to taste with any fruit syrup or with sugar, and then flavor with vanilla. Fill glass up with cracked ice and shake well together until thoroughly mixed. http://www.homemade-dessert-recipes.com/milk-shake-recipes.html</ref> [[Hamilton Beach Brands|Hamilton Beach]]'s drink mixers began being used at soda fountains in 1911 and the electric [[blender]] or drink mixer was invented by Steven Poplawski in 1922.<ref>Poplawski, Stephen J. [https://www.google.com/patents/US1480914 US Patent US1480914 \u2013 Beverage mixer], Issued February 18, 1922</ref> With the invention of the blender, milkshakes began to take their modern, whipped, aerated, and frothy form.\n\nThe use of [[malted milk]] powder in milkshakes was popularized in the US by the Chicago drugstore chain [[Walgreens]]. Malted milk powder \u2014 a mixture of [[evaporated milk]], malted [[barley]], and [[wheat flour]] \u2013 had been invented by [[William Horlick]] in 1897 for use as an easily digested restorative health drink for disabled people and children, and as an [[infant]]'s food.<ref>{{cite web |title=The History of Malted Milk Powder |url=http://www.kitchenlore.com/2011/07/history-of-malted-milk-powder.html |work=Kitchen Lore |date=July 22, 2011 |accessdate=October 10, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Wisconsin Historical\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wisconsinhistory.org/museum/exhibits/horlicks|title=Wisconsin's Malted Milk Story \u2013 Online Exhibits - Wisconsin Historical Society|website=www.wisconsinhistory.org|accessdate=June 1, 2017}}</ref> However, healthy people soon began drinking beverages made with malted milk simply for the taste,<ref name=\"Wisconsin Historical\"/> and malted milk beverages containing milk, chocolate syrup, and malt powder became a standard offering at [[soda fountain]]s. In 1922, Walgreens employee Ivar \"Pop\" Coulson made a milkshake by adding two scoops of vanilla ice cream to the standard malted milk drink recipe.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.walgreens.com/about/history/hist4.jsp |title=Walgreen's history |publisher=Walgreens.com |accessdate=October 1, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080501155205/http://www.walgreens.com/about/history/hist4.jsp |archivedate=May 1, 2008  }}</ref> This item, under the name \"Horlick's Malted Milk\", was featured by the Walgreen drugstore chain as part of a chocolate milk shake, which itself became known as a \"malted\" or \"malt\" and became one of the most popular soda-fountain drinks.<ref>[http://www.foodtimeline.org/foodicecream.html The Encyclopedia of American Food and Drink], John F. Mariani [Lebhar-Friedman:New York] 1999 (p. 196\u2013197)</ref>\n\nThe automation of milkshakes developed in the 1930s, after the invention of [[freon]]-cooled refrigerators provided a safe, reliable way of automatically making and dispensing ice cream. In 1936, inventor Earl Prince used the basic concept behind the freon-cooled automated ice cream machine to develop the Multimixer, a \"five-spindled mixer that could produce five milkshakes at once, all automatically, and dispense them at the pull of a lever into awaiting paper cups.\" {{citation needed|date=June 2013}}\n\nIn the late 1930s, several newspaper articles show that the term \"frosted\" was used to refer to milkshakes made with ice cream. In 1937, the ''[[Denton Journal]]'' in Maryland stated that \"For a 'frosted' shake, add a dash of your favorite ice cream.\" In 1939, the ''Mansfield News'' in Ohio stated that \"A frosted beverage, in the vernacular, is something good to which ice cream has been added. Example par excellence is frosted coffee\u2014that hot, tasty beverage made chilly with ice and frosty with ice cream.\"<ref>American Dialect Society CABINET, CONCRETE, FROSTED, VELVET</ref>\n\n===1940s\u20131950s===\nBy the 1950s, popular places to drink milkshakes were [[F. W. Woolworth Company|Woolworth's]] \"5 & 10\" [[lunch counter]]s, [[diner]]s, burger joints, and [[pharmacy|drugstore]] [[soda fountain]]s. These establishments often prominently displayed a shining chrome or stainless steel milkshake mixing machine.<ref>[http://www.artsparx.com/dinerstyle.asp Diner Style]. Artsparx.com. Retrieved on October 10, 2013.</ref>\n\nThese establishments made milkshakes in Hamilton Beach or similar styles of drink mixers, which had spindles and agitators that folded air into the drinks for \"smooth, fluffy results\" and served them in 12\u00bd-ounce tall, \"Y\"-shaped glasses. Soda fountain staff had their own jargon, such as \"Burn One All the Way\" (chocolate malted with chocolate ice cream), \"Twist It, Choke It, and Make It Cackle\" (chocolate malted with an egg), \"Shake One in the Hay\" (a strawberry shake), and a \"White Cow\" (a vanilla milkshake).<ref>[http://www.newyorkfirst.com/gifts/1038.html Shake One in the Hay.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100316131554/http://www.newyorkfirst.com/gifts/1038.html |date=March 16, 2010 }} New York First</ref> In the 1950s, a milkshake machine salesman named [[Ray Kroc]] bought exclusive rights to the 1930s-era Multimixer milkshake maker from inventor Earl Prince, and went on to use automated milkshake machines<ref>[http://www.jyi.org/volumes/volume7/issue1/features/cull.html Happy Meals in Kitty Hawk: How the Wright Brothers Spawned a Burger Nation]. Jyi.org. Retrieved on October 10, 2013.</ref> to speed up production at McDonald's restaurants.\n\nMilkshakes had also become popular in other parts of the world, including the [[United Kingdom]] and [[Australia]]. In Australia, [[milk bar]]s had grown popular and milkshakes were normally served lightly whipped and often in the aluminium or stainless steel cups in which they were prepared. In addition to more conventional flavors, spearmint and lime flavored milkshakes became popular in Australia.\n\n===2000s\u2013present===\n[[File:Strawberry-Mint Liquid Nitrogen Shake at HBurger in Denver.jpg|thumb|upright|This milkshake was made using [[liquid nitrogen]]. Vapor can still be seen forming at the top.]]\n\nIn 2006, the U.S. [[Agricultural Research Service]] developed reduced-sugar, low-fat milk shakes for lunch programs. The shakes have half the sugar and only 10% of the fat of commercial fast-food shakes. Schools need a milk shake machine or soft-serve ice cream machine to serve the milkshakes. The milkshakes also have added fiber and other nutrients, and they have much less lactose, which makes the shakes appropriate for some lactose-intolerant people.<ref>Konstance, Richard P. (May 2000) [https://web.archive.org/web/20040209111534/http://www.ars.usda.gov/is/AR/archive/may00/shake0500.htm \"Shaking Up the Future\"]. ''Agricultural Research'' magazine.</ref>\n\nThe U.S. sales of milkshakes, malts, and floats rose 11% in 2006, according to the industry research firm NPD Group. Christopher Muller, the director of the Center for Multi-Unit Restaurant Management at Orlando's University of Central Florida said that \"milkshakes remind us of summer, youth&nbsp;\u2014 and indulgence\", and \"they're evocative of a time gone by\".<ref name=\"usa\">[https://www.usatoday.com/money/industries/food/2007-04-24-milkshakes-usat_N.htm Fancier ways to get brain freeze.] By Bruce Horovitz, ''USA TODAY''</ref>\nMuller stated that milkshakes are an \"enormously profitable\" item for restaurants, since the drinks contain so much air. The market research firm Technomic states that about 75% of the average-priced $3.38 restaurant shake in 2006 was profit. An executive from [[Sonic Drive-In]], a U.S. chain of 1950s-style diner restaurants, calls shakes \"one of our highest-volume, revenue-producing areas\".<ref name=\"usa\"/>\n\nA 2016 article stated that chefs are trying out innovative ideas with milkshakes to keep customers interested in the drinks.<ref name=\"nrn.com\">{{cite web|url=http://beta.nrn.com/beverage-trends/sweetening-bottom-line-milkshakes|title=Sweetening the bottom line with milkshakes|date=July 18, 2016|publisher=|accessdate=June 1, 2017}}</ref> The article noted that coffee-flavored shakes are popular \"because it complements both sweet and savory\" dishes. Another trend is using different types of milk, such as [[almond milk]], [[coconut milk]], or [[hemp milk]].<ref name=\"nrn.com\"/>\n\n==Use in protests==\n{{Main|Milkshaking}}\nIn May 2019, during the build-up to the [[2019 European Parliament election in the United Kingdom|EU parliament elections in the United Kingdom]], the throwing of milkshakes emerged as a protest tactic, usually targeting right-wing politicians. The movement originated with the \"[[milkshaking]]\" of [[Tommy Robinson (activist)|Tommy Robinson]], with a second thrown later that month.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/av/uk-48156965/tommy-robinson-milkshake-thrown-over-mr-robinson|title=Milkshake thrown over Tommy Robinson|website=BBC News}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/milkshake-throwing-nigel-farage-tommy-robinson-carl-benjamin-sargon-a8922111.html|title=All the people who have been milkshaked so far this year|date=May 20, 2019|website=The Independent}}</ref>\n\nThe UK police requested that an Edinburgh [[McDonald's]] refrain from selling milkshakes on May 17 during a visit by [[Nigel Farage]]. This prompted [[Burger King]] to tweet in response: \"We're selling milkshakes all weekend. Have fun.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/food/shortcuts/2019/may/20/milkshakes-a-delicious-drink-or-the-new-symbol-of-the-resistance|title=Milkshakes: a delicious drink, or the new symbol of the resistance?|first=Guardian|last=Staff|date=May 20, 2019|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref> Burger King's tweet was later banned by the UK's [[Advertising Standards Authority (United Kingdom)|Advertising Standards Authority]], because they felt that it \"condoned the previous anti-social behaviour and encouraged further instances\", and that it was therefore an \"irresponsible\" advertisement.<ref>{{cite web |title=Burger King milkshake tweet 'encouraged' anti-social conduct |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-49895800 |website=BBC News |accessdate=October 16, 2019 |date=October 2, 2019}}</ref> At a separate visit in Newcastle on May 20, Farage had a [[Five Guys]] milkshake thrown at him.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2019/may/21/man-charged-assault-nigel-farage-milkshake-incident|title=Man charged with assault over Nigel Farage milkshake incident|first=Press|last=Association|date=May 21, 2019|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref> [[Carl Benjamin]] had a total of four milkshakes thrown at him that week.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/carl-benjamin-milkshake-salisbury-ukip-a8920846.html|title=Ukip's Carl Benjamin hit by milkshake in Salisbury in fourth attack this week|date=May 19, 2019|website=The Independent}}</ref> The act of milkshaking is similar to that of [[egging]] as a form of protest against political figures.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newstatesman.com/politics/uk/2019/05/lactose-against-intolerance-how-milkshake-became-tool-protest|title=\"Lactose Against Intolerance!\" How milkshake became a tool of protest|website=www.newstatesman.com}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\nMilkshakes in the movies have been described a \"shorthand for sweetness and goodness\".<ref name=\"denofgeek.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.denofgeek.com/movies/milkshake/22257/celebrating-milkshake-in-the-movies|title=Celebrating milkshake in the movies|publisher=|accessdate=June 1, 2017}}</ref> In ''[[All About Eve]]'', by director [[Joseph L Mankiewicz]], [[Bette Davis]]\u2019 character is unhappy to see a man she likes chatting up her young female assistant, so Davis' character orders an alcoholic [[Martini (cocktail)|Martini]], and \"then mockingly suggests [that] Eve [the young assistant] will have a milkshake\", thereby \"asserting womanhood over girlhood through milkshake's associations with virginity.\"<ref name=\"denofgeek.com\"/> Similarly, the socially awkward and nerdy character [[Steve Buscemi]] plays in ''[[Ghost World (film)|Ghost World]]'' is made fun of by a teenage girl because he orders a \"virginal vanilla milkshake\"; in ''[[Manhattan (1979 film)|Manhattan]]'', by director [[Woody Allen]], the director draws attention to the difference in age between his 42-year-old character (he also acts in the lead role) and his teenage girlfriend by having her drink a milkshake. In the film ''[[Lolita (1997 film)|Lolita]]'' in 1997, a teenage girl drinks a milkshake while she is with the middle-aged man (her mother's new boyfriend) who is attracted to her.<ref name=\"denofgeek.com\"/> [[Pulp Fiction]] has a scene in a retro-50s diner where two characters on a [[first date]] discuss the merits of a \"Five Dollar Milkshake\" (\"[[Martin and Lewis]]\" for vanilla, \"[[Amos and Andy]]\" for chocolate).\n\nThe characters from [[Archie Comics]] are often depicted drinking milkshakes. The TV series ''[[Riverdale (2017 TV series)|Riverdale]]'', inspired by the comics, depicts the characters in a 1950s-inspired local diner, Pop's Chock'lit Shoppe; to promote the show, the cast shared a milkshake during an appearance on ''[[The Tonight Show starring Jimmy Fallon]]''.<ref name=\"swartz1\">{{cite web |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2018/04/fast-food-nostalgia/558686/ |title=American Nostalgia on a Bun|last=Swartz |first=Suzie |date=April 24, 2018|website=www.theatlantic.com |publisher=The Atlantic |access-date=May 10, 2018 |quote=}}</ref>\n\n[[Master Shake]], one of the main characters from the American [[animated series]] ''[[Aqua Teen Hunger Force]]'' (also known by various [[List of alternative titles for Aqua Teen Hunger Force|alternative titles]]), is a life-sized [[anthropomorphism|anthropomorphic]] milkshake. \n\n\"[[Milkshake (song)|Milkshake]]\" is the title of a 2003 [[contemporary R&B|R&B]]\u2013[[electro music|electro]] song written and produced by [[The Neptunes]] for American singer [[Kelis]]' third studio album, ''[[Tasty (Kelis album)|Tasty]]''. It reached the top ten in the United Kingdom, Australia, and the [[Netherlands]], and became Kelis' biggest success to date on [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] in the United States, peaking at number three. The song became an [[Internet meme]] following the release of [[Paul Thomas Anderson]]'s 2007 film ''[[There Will Be Blood]]'', in which scenes from the film (most notably from its famous \"I drink your milkshake\" scene) were edited to the song.<ref name=\"oil\">{{cite news|url=http://www.laweekly.com/film+tv/film/paul-thomas-anderson-blood-sweat-and-tears/18140/?page=2|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080123075316/http://www.laweekly.com/film+tv/film/paul-thomas-anderson-blood-sweat-and-tears/18140/?page=2|archivedate=January 23, 2008|title=Paul Thomas Anderson: Blood, Sweat and Tears|work=[[LA Weekly]] |accessdate=July 7, 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"oil2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/movies/news/2008-02-03-blood-milkshake_N.htm |title='Blood' fans drink up milkshake catchphrase |accessdate=February 24, 2008|last=Bowles|first=Scott|date=February 3, 2008|work=[[USA Today]]}}</ref> The line became something of a [[catchphrase]] for the film and gained moderate recognition in [[popular culture]] following the film's release.<ref name=\"catchphrase\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/article/305756 |title=It's bottoms up to our Oscars drinking game |accessdate=February 24, 2008|last=Mudhar|first=Raju|date=February 23, 2008|work=[[The Toronto Star]]}}</ref>\n\nThe term \"[[milkshake duck]]\" refers to the social media trend where \"the internet rushes en masse to embrace something or someone as cute, worthy, fun or funny\" (such as a duck that drinks milkshakes), but \"then just as quickly drops it, when it\u2019s revealed to somehow be unpleasantly complicated\"; the paper called the term \"useful shorthand\" for when a \"favourite [concept] is revealed to be problematic\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2017/dec/18/what-is-a-milkshake-duck-and-why-isnt-it-the-word-of-the-year |title=What is a milkshake duck? And why isn't it the word of the year? |last= Hunt |first=Elle |date=December 18, 2017 |work=The Guardian |location=London |access-date=May 9, 2018 |quote=}}</ref> \n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Drink}}\n* [[Health shake]]\n* [[Smoothie]]\n* [[Haldi Ka Doodh]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{cookbook}}\n{{Commons category-inline|Milkshakes}}\n{{Ice cream}}\n{{Milk navbox}}\n\n[[Category:American cuisine]]\n[[Category:Cold drinks]]\n[[Category:Drinks]]\n[[Category:Flavored milk|Shake]]\n[[Category:Ice cream]]\n[[Category:Milk-based drinks]]\n[[Category:Non-alcoholic drinks]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other uses}}\n{{short description|cold dairy beverage}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox food\n| name             = Milkshake\n| image            = Strawberry milkshake.jpg\n| caption          = A [[Johnny Rockets]] [[strawberry]] milkshake topped with [[whipped cream]] and strawberry [[syrup]]\n| alternate_name   = Thick shake, frappe\n| country          = [[United States]]\n| region           =\n| creator          =\n| course           =\n| type             = [[Drink|Beverage]]\n| served           =\n| main_ingredient  = [[Milk]], [[ice cream]], and flavorings or sweeteners\n| variations       =\n| calories         =\n| other            =\n}}\n\nA '''milkshake''', or simply '''shake''', is a drink that is usually made by blending [[milk]], [[ice cream]], and flavorings or sweeteners such as [[butterscotch]], [[caramel]] sauce, [[chocolate syrup]], or [[fruit syrup]] into a thick, sweet, cold mixture.\n\n==Preparation==\n[[File:Soda jerker flipping ice cream into malted milk shakes. Corpus Christi, Texas.jpg|right|thumb|A [[soda jerk]] throws a scoop of ice cream into a steel mixing cup while making a milkshake. On the counter behind him another mixing cup, shake mixers, and a pot of \"[[Borden (company)|Borden's]] Malted Milk\" powder are visible.]]\nFull-service restaurants, [[ice cream shop]]s, [[soda fountain]]s, [[diner]]s, and people at home usually prepare and mix the shake by hand from scoops of ice cream and milk in a [[blender]] or drink mixer. Hand-blended milkshakes are traditionally made from any flavor of ice cream; additional flavorings, such as [[chocolate syrup]], [[barley malt syrup|malt syrup]], or [[malted milk]] powder, can be added prior to mixing. This allows a greater variety than is available in machine-made shakes. \n\nMany [[fast food]] outlets do not make shakes by hand with ice cream; instead, they make shakes in automatic milkshake machines which freeze and serve a pre-made milkshake mixture consisting of milk, a sweetened flavoring agent, and a thickening agent. These are similar to [[soft-serve]] ice cream machines, but keep the shake at a drinkable consistency.\n\n==Terminology==\nTerminology around the distinction between a milkshake that uses ice cream and other forms of [[flavored milk]] varies regionally. An ice cream-based milkshake may be called a ''thick shake'' to distinguish it. In parts of [[New England]] and eastern Canada, the name ''frappe'' ({{IPAc-en|f|r|\u00e6|\u02c8|p|e\u026a}} {{respell|fra|PAY}}) is used.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dictionary.cambridge.org/us/pronunciation/english/frappe|title=How to pronounce frapp\u00e9 in English|website=dictionary.cambridge.org|accessdate=June 1, 2017}}</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20010618021334/http://bartleby.com/61/66/M0296600.html milk shake]. The American Heritage Dictionary of the English Language: Fourth Edition. 2000</ref><ref>Seavey, Aimee, Digital Editor, Yankee Magazine http://www.yankeemagazine.com/article/new-england-101/milk-shakes-frappes-cabinets</ref> A milkshake containing malted milk powder is sometimes called a ''malt''. The term  ''concrete'' is used for particularly thick milkshakes that do not spill when turned upside down, such as at the restaurant [[Culver's]].<ref>American Dialect Society CABINET, CONCRETE, FROSTED, VELVET\nText accompanying illustration on a poster advertising Hood's Ice Cream (observed in Hancock Pharmacy, State and Hancock Sts., Springfield, Mass., September 30, 1952).</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Milkshakes at Mels Diner.jpg|thumb|left|A strawberry and a chocolate shake, each topped with [[whipped cream]], [[sprinkles]], and a [[maraschino cherry]]]]\n\n===1880s\u20131930s===\nWhen the term \"milkshake\" was first used in print in 1885, milkshakes were an alcoholic [[whiskey]] drink that has been described as a \"sturdy, healthful [[eggnog]] type of drink, with eggs, whiskey, etc., served as a tonic as well as a treat\".<ref name=\"stuart\">Flexner, Stuart Berg (1982) ''Listening to America'', Simon & Schuster: New York, p. 178, {{ISBN|0671248952}}</ref> However, by 1900, the term referred to \"wholesome drinks made with [[chocolate]], [[strawberry]], or [[vanilla]] [[syrup]]s.\" By the \"early 1900s people were asking for the new treat, often with ice cream.\" By the 1930s, milkshakes were a popular drink at [[malt shop]]s, which were the \"typical [[soda fountain]] of the period ... used by students as a meeting place or hangout.\"<ref name=\"stuart\"/>\n\nThe history of the electric blender, malted milk drinks, and milkshakes are interconnected. Before the widespread availability of electric blenders, milkshake-type drinks were more like eggnog, or they were a hand-shaken mixture of crushed ice and milk, sugar, and flavorings.<ref>Vanilla Milk Shake Recipe from the \"Second Edition of The Neighborhood Cookbook\" published by the Council of Jewish Women, Portland, in 1914. Fill a glass two-thirds full of milk, sweeten to taste with any fruit syrup or with sugar, and then flavor with vanilla. Fill glass up with cracked ice and shake well together until thoroughly mixed. http://www.homemade-dessert-recipes.com/milk-shake-recipes.html</ref> [[Hamilton Beach Brands|Hamilton Beach]]'s drink mixers began being used at soda fountains in 1911 and the electric [[blender]] or drink mixer was invented by Steven Poplawski in 1922.<ref>Poplawski, Stephen J. [https://www.google.com/patents/US1480914 US Patent US1480914 \u2013 Beverage mixer], Issued February 18, 1922</ref> With the invention of the blender, milkshakes began to take their modern, whipped, aerated, and frothy form.\n\nThe use of [[malted milk]] powder in milkshakes was popularized in the US by the Chicago drugstore chain [[Walgreens]]. Malted milk powder \u2014 a mixture of [[evaporated milk]], malted [[barley]], and [[wheat flour]] \u2013 had been invented by [[William Horlick]] in 1897 for use as an easily digested restorative health drink for disabled people and children, and as an [[infant]]'s food.<ref>{{cite web |title=The History of Malted Milk Powder |url=http://www.kitchenlore.com/2011/07/history-of-malted-milk-powder.html |work=Kitchen Lore |date=July 22, 2011 |accessdate=October 10, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Wisconsin Historical\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wisconsinhistory.org/museum/exhibits/horlicks|title=Wisconsin's Malted Milk Story \u2013 Online Exhibits - Wisconsin Historical Society|website=www.wisconsinhistory.org|accessdate=June 1, 2017}}</ref> However, healthy people soon began drinking beverages made with malted milk simply for the taste,<ref name=\"Wisconsin Historical\"/> and malted milk beverages containing milk, chocolate syrup, and malt powder became a standard offering at [[soda fountain]]s. In 1922, Walgreens employee Ivar \"Pop\" Coulson made a milkshake by adding two scoops of vanilla ice cream to the standard malted milk drink recipe.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.walgreens.com/about/history/hist4.jsp |title=Walgreen's history |publisher=Walgreens.com |accessdate=October 1, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080501155205/http://www.walgreens.com/about/history/hist4.jsp |archivedate=May 1, 2008  }}</ref> This item, under the name \"Horlick's Malted Milk\", was featured by the Walgreen drugstore chain as part of a chocolate milk shake, which itself became known as a \"malted\" or \"malt\" and became one of the most popular soda-fountain drinks.<ref>[http://www.foodtimeline.org/foodicecream.html The Encyclopedia of American Food and Drink], John F. Mariani [Lebhar-Friedman:New York] 1999 (p. 196\u2013197)</ref>\n\nThe automation of milkshakes developed in the 1930s, after the invention of [[freon]]-cooled refrigerators provided a safe, reliable way of automatically making and dispensing ice cream. In 1936, inventor Earl Prince used the basic concept behind the freon-cooled automated ice cream machine to develop the Multimixer, a \"five-spindled mixer that could produce five milkshakes at once, all automatically, and dispense them at the pull of a lever into awaiting paper cups.\" {{citation needed|date=June 2013}}\n\nIn the late 1930s, several newspaper articles show that the term \"frosted\" was used to refer to milkshakes made with ice cream. In 1937, the ''[[Denton Journal]]'' in Maryland stated that \"For a 'frosted' shake, add a dash of your favorite ice cream.\" In 1939, the ''Mansfield News'' in Ohio stated that \"A frosted beverage, in the vernacular, is something good to which ice cream has been added. Example par excellence is frosted coffee\u2014that hot, tasty beverage made chilly with ice and frosty with ice cream.\"<ref>American Dialect Society CABINET, CONCRETE, FROSTED, VELVET</ref>\n\n===1940s\u20131950s===\nBy the 1950s, popular places to drink milkshakes were [[F. W. Woolworth Company|Woolworth's]] \"5 & 10\" [[lunch counter]]s, [[diner]]s, burger joints, and [[pharmacy|drugstore]] [[soda fountain]]s. These establishments often prominently displayed a shining chrome or stainless steel milkshake mixing machine.<ref>[http://www.artsparx.com/dinerstyle.asp Diner Style]. Artsparx.com. Retrieved on October 10, 2013.</ref>\n\nThese establishments made milkshakes in Hamilton Beach or similar styles of drink mixers, which had spindles and agitators that folded air into the drinks for \"smooth, fluffy results\" and served them in 12\u00bd-ounce tall, \"Y\"-shaped glasses. Soda fountain staff had their own jargon, such as \"Burn One All the Way\" (chocolate malted with chocolate ice cream), \"Twist It, Choke It, and Make It Cackle\" (chocolate malted with an egg), \"Shake One in the Hay\" (a strawberry shake), and a \"White Cow\" (a vanilla milkshake).<ref>[http://www.newyorkfirst.com/gifts/1038.html Shake One in the Hay.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100316131554/http://www.newyorkfirst.com/gifts/1038.html |date=March 16, 2010 }} New York First</ref> In the 1950s, a milkshake machine salesman named [[Ray Kroc]] bought exclusive rights to the 1930s-era Multimixer milkshake maker from inventor Earl Prince, and went on to use automated milkshake machines<ref>[http://www.jyi.org/volumes/volume7/issue1/features/cull.html Happy Meals in Kitty Hawk: How the Wright Brothers Spawned a Burger Nation]. Jyi.org. Retrieved on October 10, 2013.</ref> to speed up production at McDonald's restaurants.\n\nMilkshakes had also become popular in other parts of the world, including the [[United Kingdom]] and [[Australia]]. In Australia, [[milk bar]]s had grown popular and milkshakes were normally served lightly whipped and often in the aluminium or stainless steel cups in which they were prepared. In addition to more conventional flavors, spearmint and lime flavored milkshakes became popular in Australia.\n\n===2000s\u2013present===\n[[File:Strawberry-Mint Liquid Nitrogen Shake at HBurger in Denver.jpg|thumb|upright|This milkshake was made using [[liquid nitrogen]]. Vapor can still be seen forming at the top.]]\n\nIn 2006, the U.S. [[Agricultural Research Service]] developed reduced-sugar, low-fat milk shakes for lunch programs. The shakes have half the sugar and only 10% of the fat of commercial fast-food shakes. Schools need a milk shake machine or soft-serve ice cream machine to serve the milkshakes. The milkshakes also have added fiber and other nutrients, and they have much less lactose, which makes the shakes appropriate for some lactose-intolerant people.<ref>Konstance, Richard P. (May 2000) [https://web.archive.org/web/20040209111534/http://www.ars.usda.gov/is/AR/archive/may00/shake0500.htm \"Shaking Up the Future\"]. ''Agricultural Research'' magazine.</ref>\n\nThe U.S. sales of milkshakes, malts, and floats rose 11% in 2006, according to the industry research firm NPD Group. Christopher Muller, the director of the Center for Multi-Unit Restaurant Management at Orlando's University of Central Florida said that \"milkshakes remind us of summer, youth&nbsp;\u2014 and indulgence\", and \"they're evocative of a time gone by\".<ref name=\"usa\">[https://www.usatoday.com/money/industries/food/2007-04-24-milkshakes-usat_N.htm Fancier ways to get brain freeze.] By Bruce Horovitz, ''USA TODAY''</ref>\nMuller stated that milkshakes are an \"enormously profitable\" item for restaurants, since the drinks contain so much air. The market research firm Technomic states that about 75% of the average-priced $3.38 restaurant shake in 2006 was profit. An executive from [[Sonic Drive-In]], a U.S. chain of 1950s-style diner restaurants, calls shakes \"one of our highest-volume, revenue-producing areas\".<ref name=\"usa\"/>\n\nA 2016 article stated that chefs are trying out innovative ideas with milkshakes to keep customers interested in the drinks.<ref name=\"nrn.com\">{{cite web|url=http://beta.nrn.com/beverage-trends/sweetening-bottom-line-milkshakes|title=Sweetening the bottom line with milkshakes|date=July 18, 2016|publisher=|accessdate=June 1, 2017}}</ref> The article noted that coffee-flavored shakes are popular \"because it complements both sweet and savory\" dishes. Another trend is using different types of milk, such as [[almond milk]], [[coconut milk]], or [[hemp milk]].<ref name=\"nrn.com\"/>\n\n==Use in protests==\n{{Main|Milkshaking}}\nIn May 2019, during the build-up to the [[2019 European Parliament election in the United Kingdom|EU parliament elections in the United Kingdom]], the throwing of milkshakes emerged as a protest tactic, usually targeting right-wing politicians. The movement originated with the \"[[milkshaking]]\" of [[Tommy Robinson (activist)|Tommy Robinson]], with a second thrown later that month.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/av/uk-48156965/tommy-robinson-milkshake-thrown-over-mr-robinson|title=Milkshake thrown over Tommy Robinson|website=BBC News}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/milkshake-throwing-nigel-farage-tommy-robinson-carl-benjamin-sargon-a8922111.html|title=All the people who have been milkshaked so far this year|date=May 20, 2019|website=The Independent}}</ref>\n\nThe UK police requested that an Edinburgh [[McDonald's]] refrain from selling milkshakes on May 17 during a visit by [[Nigel Farage]]. This prompted [[Burger King]] to tweet in response: \"We're selling milkshakes all weekend. Have fun.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/food/shortcuts/2019/may/20/milkshakes-a-delicious-drink-or-the-new-symbol-of-the-resistance|title=Milkshakes: a delicious drink, or the new symbol of the resistance?|first=Guardian|last=Staff|date=May 20, 2019|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref> Burger King's tweet was later banned by the UK's [[Advertising Standards Authority (United Kingdom)|Advertising Standards Authority]], because they felt that it \"condoned the previous anti-social behaviour and encouraged further instances\", and that it was therefore an \"irresponsible\" advertisement.<ref>{{cite web |title=Burger King milkshake tweet 'encouraged' anti-social conduct |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-49895800 |website=BBC News |accessdate=October 16, 2019 |date=October 2, 2019}}</ref> At a separate visit in Newcastle on May 20, Farage had a [[Five Guys]] milkshake thrown at him.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2019/may/21/man-charged-assault-nigel-farage-milkshake-incident|title=Man charged with assault over Nigel Farage milkshake incident|first=Press|last=Association|date=May 21, 2019|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref> [[Carl Benjamin]] had a total of four milkshakes thrown at him that week.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/carl-benjamin-milkshake-salisbury-ukip-a8920846.html|title=Ukip's Carl Benjamin hit by milkshake in Salisbury in fourth attack this week|date=May 19, 2019|website=The Independent}}</ref> The act of milkshaking is similar to that of [[egging]] as a form of protest against political figures.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newstatesman.com/politics/uk/2019/05/lactose-against-intolerance-how-milkshake-became-tool-protest|title=\"Lactose Against Intolerance!\" How milkshake became a tool of protest|website=www.newstatesman.com}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\nMilkshakes in the movies have been described a \"shorthand for sweetness and goodness\".<ref name=\"denofgeek.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.denofgeek.com/movies/milkshake/22257/celebrating-milkshake-in-the-movies|title=Celebrating milkshake in the movies|publisher=|accessdate=June 1, 2017}}</ref> In ''[[All About Eve]]'', by director [[Joseph L Mankiewicz]], [[Bette Davis]]\u2019 character is unhappy to see a man she likes chatting up her young female assistant, so Davis' character orders an alcoholic [[Martini (cocktail)|Martini]], and \"then mockingly suggests [that] Eve [the young assistant] will have a milkshake\", thereby \"asserting womanhood over girlhood through milkshake's associations with virginity.\"<ref name=\"denofgeek.com\"/> Similarly, the socially awkward and nerdy character [[Steve Buscemi]] plays in ''[[Ghost World (film)|Ghost World]]'' is made fun of by a teenage girl because he orders a \"virginal vanilla milkshake\"; in ''[[Manhattan (1979 film)|Manhattan]]'', by director [[Woody Allen]], the director draws attention to the difference in age between his 42-year-old character (he also acts in the lead role) and his teenage girlfriend by having her drink a milkshake. In the film ''[[Lolita (1997 film)|Lolita]]'' in 1997, a teenage girl drinks a milkshake while she is with the middle-aged man (her mother's new boyfriend) who is attracted to her.<ref name=\"denofgeek.com\"/> [[Pulp Fiction]] has a scene in a retro-50s diner where two characters on a [[first date]] discuss the merits of a \"Five Dollar Milkshake\" (\"[[Martin and Lewis]]\" for vanilla, \"[[Amos and Andy]]\" for chocolate).\n\nThe characters from [[Archie Comics]] are often depicted drinking milkshakes. The TV series ''[[Riverdale (2017 TV series)|Riverdale]]'', inspired by the comics, depicts the characters in a 1950s-inspired local diner, Pop's Chock'lit Shoppe; to promote the show, the cast shared a milkshake during an appearance on ''[[The Tonight Show starring Jimmy Fallon]]''.<ref name=\"swartz1\">{{cite web |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2018/04/fast-food-nostalgia/558686/ |title=American Nostalgia on a Bun|last=Swartz |first=Suzie |date=April 24, 2018|website=www.theatlantic.com |publisher=The Atlantic |access-date=May 10, 2018 |quote=}}</ref>\n\n[[Master Shake]], one of the main characters from the American [[animated series]] ''[[Aqua Teen Hunger Force]]'' (also known by various [[List of alternative titles for Aqua Teen Hunger Force|alternative titles]]), is a life-sized [[anthropomorphism|anthropomorphic]] milkshake. \n\n\"[[Milkshake (song)|Milkshake]]\" is the title of a 2003 [[contemporary R&B|R&B]]\u2013[[electro music|electro]] song written and produced by [[The Neptunes]] for American singer [[Kelis]]' third studio album, ''[[Tasty (Kelis album)|Tasty]]''. It reached the top ten in the United Kingdom, Australia, and the [[Netherlands]], and became Kelis' biggest success to date on [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] in the United States, peaking at number three. The song became an [[Internet meme]] following the release of [[Paul Thomas Anderson]]'s 2007 film ''[[There Will Be Blood]]'', in which scenes from the film (most notably from its famous \"I drink your milkshake\" scene) were edited to the song.<ref name=\"oil\">{{cite news|url=http://www.laweekly.com/film+tv/film/paul-thomas-anderson-blood-sweat-and-tears/18140/?page=2|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080123075316/http://www.laweekly.com/film+tv/film/paul-thomas-anderson-blood-sweat-and-tears/18140/?page=2|archivedate=January 23, 2008|title=Paul Thomas Anderson: Blood, Sweat and Tears|work=[[LA Weekly]] |accessdate=July 7, 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"oil2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/movies/news/2008-02-03-blood-milkshake_N.htm |title='Blood' fans drink up milkshake catchphrase |accessdate=February 24, 2008|last=Bowles|first=Scott|date=February 3, 2008|work=[[USA Today]]}}</ref> The line became something of a [[catchphrase]] for the film and gained moderate recognition in [[popular culture]] following the film's release.<ref name=\"catchphrase\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/article/305756 |title=It's bottoms up to our Oscars drinking game |accessdate=February 24, 2008|last=Mudhar|first=Raju|date=February 23, 2008|work=[[The Toronto Star]]}}</ref>\n\nThe term \"[[milkshake duck]]\" refers to the social media trend where \"the internet rushes en masse to embrace something or someone as cute, worthy, fun or funny\" (such as a duck that drinks milkshakes), but \"then just as quickly drops it, when it\u2019s revealed to somehow be unpleasantly complicated\"; the paper called the term \"useful shorthand\" for when a \"favourite [concept] is revealed to be problematic\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2017/dec/18/what-is-a-milkshake-duck-and-why-isnt-it-the-word-of-the-year |title=What is a milkshake duck? And why isn't it the word of the year? |last= Hunt |first=Elle |date=December 18, 2017 |work=The Guardian |location=London |access-date=May 9, 2018 |quote=}}</ref> \n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Drink}}\n* [[Health shake]]\n* [[Smoothie]]\n* [[Haldi Ka Doodh]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{cookbook}}\n{{Commons category-inline|Milkshakes}}\n{{Ice cream}}\n{{Milk navbox}}\n\n[[Category:American cuisine]]\n[[Category:Cold drinks]]\n[[Category:Drinks]]\n[[Category:Flavored milk|Shake]]\n[[Category:Ice cream]]\n[[Category:Milk-based drinks]]\n[[Category:Non-alcoholic drinks]]\n", "name_user": "80.189.203.137", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Milkshake"}
{"title_page": "R\u0103d\u0103u\u021bi", "text_new": "{{for|the former administrative subdivision of Romania|R\u0103d\u0103u\u021bi County}}\n{{Infobox Romanian subdivision\n|type                   = municipality\n|county                 = Suceava\n|population_total       = auto\n|map_caption            = Location in Suceava County\n|official_name=R\u0103d\u0103u\u021bi\n|image_shield=ROU SV Radauti CoA.png\n|image_map              = Radauti jud Suceava.png\n|image_skyline=Fosta prefectur\u0103 \u0219i hotel, R\u0103d\u0103u\u021bi (2).JPG\n|image_caption=Union Square in downtown R\u0103d\u0103u\u021bi\n|leader_name=Nistor T\u0103tar<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.2016bec.ro/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/SIAL2016_P_Lista_Moc-2.xlsx |title=Results of the 2016 local elections |publisher=Central Electoral Bureau |accessdate=2020-04-03 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|leader_party=PSD\n|area_total_km2=32.30\n|coordinates            = {{coord|47|50|33|N|25|55|9|E|region:RO|display=inline,title}}\n|website=[http://primariaradauti.ro/ Official site]\n}}\n\n'''R\u0103d\u0103u\u021bi''' ({{IPA-ro|r\u0259d\u0259\u02c8ut\u0361s\u02b2}}; {{lang-de|Radautz}}; {{lang-hu|Rad\u00f3c}}; {{lang-pl|Radowce}}; {{lang-uk|\u0420\u0430\u0434\u0456\u0432\u0446\u0456}}, ''Radivtsi''; {{lang-yi|\u05e8\u05d0\u05b7\u05d3\u05e2\u05f0\u05d9\u05e5}} ''Radevits''; {{lang-tr|Radovi\u00e7e}}) is a [[municipiu|city]] in [[Suceava County]], north-eastern [[Romania]]. It is situated in the historical region of [[Bukovina]]. R\u0103d\u0103u\u021bi is the third largest urban settlement in the county, with a population of 23,822 inhabitants, according to the 2011 census. It was declared a municipality in 1995, along with two other cities in Suceava County: [[F\u0103lticeni]] and [[C\u00e2mpulung Moldovenesc]]. R\u0103d\u0103u\u021bi covers an area of 32,30&nbsp;km\u00b2 and it was the capital of former [[R\u0103d\u0103u\u021bi County]] (until 1950).\n\n==Administration and local politics==\n\n=== Town council ===\n\nThe town's current local council has the following political composition, according to the results of the [[2016 Romanian local elections]]:\n\n{| cellpadding=\"2\" cellspacing=\"0\" border=\"1\" class=\"wikitable\"\n! style=\"background:#ccc\" | &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; \n! style=\"background:#ccc\" | Party\n! style=\"background:#ccc\" | Seats\n! style=\"background:#ccc\" colspan=\"7\" | Current Council\n|-\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PSD}} | &nbsp;\n| [[Social Democratic Party (Romania)|Social Democratic Party (PSD)]]\n| style=\"text-align: right\" | '''7'''\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PSD}} | &nbsp; \n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PSD}} | &nbsp; \n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PSD}} | &nbsp; \n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PSD}} | &nbsp; \n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PSD}} | &nbsp; \n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PSD}} | &nbsp; \n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PSD}} | &nbsp; \n|-\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PNL}} | &nbsp;\n| [[National Liberal Party (Romania)|National Liberal Party (PNL)]]\n| style=\"text-align: right\" | '''5'''\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PNL}} | &nbsp;\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PNL}} | &nbsp;\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PNL}} | &nbsp;\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PNL}} | &nbsp;\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PNL}} | &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n|-\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/ALDE}} | &nbsp;\n| [[Alliance of Liberals and Democrats (Romania)|Alliance of Liberals and Democrats (ALDE)]]\n| style=\"text-align: right\" | '''3'''\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/ALDE}} | &nbsp;\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/ALDE}} | &nbsp;\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/ALDE}} | &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n|-\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PMP}} | &nbsp;\n| [[People's Movement Party|People's Movement Party (PMP)]]\n| style=\"text-align: right\" | '''2'''\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PMP}} | &nbsp;\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PMP}} | &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n|-\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/Independent}} | &nbsp;\n| [[Independent politician|Union for R\u0103d\u0103u\u021bi (UPR)]]\n| style=\"text-align: right\" | '''2'''\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/Independent}} | &nbsp;\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/Independent}} | &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n|-\n|}\n\n==Geography==\nR\u0103d\u0103u\u021bi is situated in [[Bukovina]], on a plain between the [[Suceava River|Suceava]] and [[Sucevi\u021ba River|Sucevi\u021ba]] rivers, {{convert|37|km|mi|abbr=on}} north-west from [[Suceava]], the county capital. The city is located in the depression with the same name, at {{convert|375|m|yd|abbr=off}} altitude. It is one of the oldest settlements in Moldavia, known since the 15th century. The towns of [[Siret]], [[Solca]], [[Mili\u0219\u0103u\u021bi]] and [[Vicovu de Sus]] are located relatively close to the city, in the R\u0103d\u0103u\u021bi urban area of influence.\n\n==Demographics==\n{{Historical populations\n|source = Austrian and Romanian census data and/or official estimates\n|1910 |16,535\n|1930 |16,788\n|1948 |14,530\n|1956 |15,949\n|1966 |18,580\n|1977 |21,869\n|1992 |31,074\n|2002 |27,633\n|2011 |23,822\n}}\n\nR\u0103d\u0103u\u0163i reached its peak population in 1992, when more than 31,000 people were living within the city limits. As of 2016, the town of R\u0103d\u0103u\u021bi was the second most populated urban settlement in [[Suceava County]], after the county capital, [[Suceava]].<ref name=\"INSSER2016\">{{cite web|url=http://www.insse.ro/cms/ro/content/popula%C5%A3ia-rom%C3%A2niei-pe-localitati-la-1-ianuarie-2016|title=Popula\u0163ia Rom\u00e2niei pe localitati la 1 ianuarie 2016|date=6 June 2016|accessdate=27 October 2017|publisher=[[National Institute of Statistics (Romania)|INSSE]]|language=Romanian|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171027131447/http://www.insse.ro/cms/ro/content/popula%C5%A3ia-rom%C3%A2niei-pe-localitati-la-1-ianuarie-2016|archive-date=2017-10-27|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nAt the 2011 census, R\u0103d\u0103u\u021bi had a population of 23,822 inhabitants: 96.97% of inhabitants were [[Romanians|ethnic Romanians]], 0.89% [[Russians]] and [[Lipovans]], 0.88% [[Roma in Romania|Roma]], 0.54% [[Ukrainians]] and 0.23% [[Germans of Romania|Germans]] <small>([[Bukovina Germans]])</small>. 83.4% were [[Romanian Orthodox]], 9.1% [[Pentecostal Union of Romania|Pentecostal]], 3.1% [[Roman Catholic]], 0.9% stated they belonged to another religion, 0.8% were [[Romanian Church United with Rome, Greek-Catholic|Greek-Catholic]] and 0.7% each [[Baptist Union of Romania|Baptist]] and [[Lipovan Orthodox Old-Rite Church|Lipovan Orthodox]].\n\n==History==\n[[File:Radautz 1873 Radauti.jpg|thumb|right|150px|Austrian KK stamp, issue 1873, cancelled at ''Radautz'']]\nThe mention of \"Radomir's village\" (as part of a review of [[boyar]] property in the area) in a 1392 document (''uric'') is generally{{who|date=January 2017}} believed to be the town's first mention, and indication of the origin of the name ''R\u0103d\u0103u\u021bi'' (other theories state that the settlement had its origins in earlier periods, and that the name is a [[Slavic languages|Slavic]]-influenced derivative of the [[Latin]] word ''Rottacenum'', as allegedly used by soldiers in the [[Roman Empire|Roman]] garrison in [[Siret]]).<ref>{{cite book | first=Lawrence | last=Winkler | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=F4n4a29AtT4C&pg=PA378&lpg=PA378&dq=Rottacenum&source=bl&ots=wfiDg1iApN&sig=S1rqD6JF0QLxWo1RLJC90v2rQPA&hl=sv&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwim6-ellLjRAhWFWhoKHftuDyc4ChDoAQgYMAA#v=onepage&q=Rottacenum&f=false | title=Between the Cartwheels (Orion's Cartwheels Book 2) | accessdate=January 10, 2017 | website=Google Books | year=2012 | page=378| asin=B009JDN4ES }}</ref>{{unreliable source?|date=January 2017}} The oldest mention of R\u0103d\u0103u\u021bi as such dates from 1413, in a document issued by Moldavian Prince [[Alexandru cel Bun]].\n\nBy the middle of the 14th century, R\u0103d\u0103u\u021bi was already a flourishing settlement, the seat of a prominent [[Eastern Orthodox Church|Eastern Orthodox]] church during the times of [[Bogdan I of Moldova|Bogdan I]] (1359\u20131365), and subsequently a [[Diocese|bishopric]]. Around the St. Nicholas church ([[Bogdana Monastery]]), archaeologists have uncovered a [[Archaeological stratigraphy|habitation layer]] preceding Bogdan's period of rule, one which could point to the existence of a local center prior to the [[foundation of Moldavia]].\n\nAwarded the [[Town privileges|privilege]] of organizing [[fair]]s, R\u0103d\u0103u\u021bi evolved due to its favorable location midway between the [[Carpathian Mountains|Carpathians]] and the tableland area (with traders from both regions establishing contact in the local market). The fairs at R\u0103d\u0103u\u021bi have been dated to the time of [[Stephen III of Moldavia|Stephen the Great]] (a document from 1481; however, since the mention includes details of Stephen's intervention in solving a commercial dispute, it is possible that the fairs were well established by then).\n\nR\u0103d\u0103u\u021bi has a cathedral (built 1402) with the tombs of several Moldavian princes.<ref name=EB1911>{{Cite EB1911 |wstitle=Radautz |volume=22 |page=783}}</ref> R\u0103d\u0103u\u021bi was also the seat of a Greek bishopric, moved to [[Chernivtsi]] in 1786.<ref name=EB1911/>\n\nR\u0103d\u0103u\u021bi was one of the largest cities of the Duchy of [[Bukovina]] during the period of [[Habsburg Monarchy|Habsburg]] administration (1775\u20131918). During that time it saw a high level of [[Germans of Romania|German]] (especially [[Swabians|Swabian]]) immigration.\n\n==Jewish history of R\u0103d\u0103u\u0163i==\n{{main|History of the Jews in Romania}}\nA Jewish community was present before the Habsburg takeover, and is attested to have been overseen by a ''[[starost]]''.\n\nMany Jews fleeing the [[Galicia (Central Europe)|Kingdom of Galicia and Lodomeria]] (as well as other Habsburg areas) from intense persecution and [[anti-Semitism]] during the Middle Ages settled in R\u0103d\u0103u\u0163i. The community was allowed a degree of self-administration, and witnessed a period of prosperity and cultural effervescence during the 19th century.\n\nThe majority of R\u0103d\u0103u\u021bi's Jewish population was exterminated during the [[Holocaust]]. Persecutions became widespread around 1938, when Jews were harassed and attacked by authorities under the [[Octavian Goga]] government; they were confirmed by anti-Semitic legislation passed by the [[Ion Gigurtu]] cabinet, and, in late 1940, exceptionally violent following the establishment of the [[National Legionary State]]. In October 1941, all Jews present in R\u0103d\u0103u\u021bi (more than 10,000) were deported to [[concentration camp]]s in [[Transnistria]].<ref name=\"JEWISH_RADAUTI\">{{cite web | url = http://www.jewishgen.org/yizkor/pinkas_romania/rom2_00516.html | title = Translation of ''R\u0103d\u0103u\u021bi'' chapter from ''Encyclopedia of Jewish Communities in Romania'', Vol. 2 | year = 1980 | accessdate = January 29, 2013 | publisher = Yad Vashem, Jerusalim }}</ref>\n\n==Bogdana Monastery==\nThe Princely Church at R\u0103d\u0103u\u0163i contained the graves of [[Bogdan I]] and his son [[La\u0163cu]], both [[Voivode]]s/[[Prince]]s of [[Moldavia]], as well as a later ruler, [[Roman I of Moldavia]]. Is the oldest monastery from [[Moldova]] and [[Bucovina]] (1365). Inside the monastery there are 14 tombs (like Bogdan I (1359\u20131365), La\u021bcu Voievod (1365\u20131373), Roman I (1391\u20131394), \u0218tefan I (1394\u20131399), Bogdan, the brother Alexandru cel Bun, Bogdan, son of Alexandru cel Bun and others.\n\n== Twin towns \u2014 Sister cities ==\n\nR\u0103d\u0103u\u021bi is [[Twin towns and sister cities|twinned]] with:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://primariaradauti.ro/radauti/orase-infratite/|title=Prim\u0103ria R\u0103d\u0103u\u021bi - Ora\u0219e \u00eenfr\u0103\u021bite (in Romanian)|work=Prim\u0103ria R\u0103d\u0103u\u021bi}}</ref>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|\n* {{flagicon|DEU}} [[Beilstein, W\u00fcrttemberg|Beilstein]], [[Germany]]\n* {{flagicon|FRA}} [[Pontault-Combault]], [[France]]\n* {{flagicon|MDA}} [[Drochia]], [[Moldova]]\n* {{flagicon|MDA}} [[Briceni]], [[Moldova]]\n* {{flagicon|POR}} [[Caminha]], [[Portugal]]\n* {{flagicon|POL}} [[Gliwice]], [[Poland]]\n* {{flagicon|CYP}} [[Kyrenia]], [[Cyprus]]\n* {{flagicon|ITA}} [[Ragusa, Sicily|Ragusa]], [[Italy]]\n|}\n\n==Natives==\n* [[Avigdor Arikha]] - Israeli painter\n* [[Emil Armin]] - American artist \n* [[Alexandru Bodnar]] - athlete\n* [[Heinrich G\u00e4rtner (cinematographer)|Heinrich G\u00e4rtner]] - cinematographer\n* [[Irina Lauric]] - sprint canoeist\n* Iacov Putneanul - [[Metropolitan of Moldavia and Bukovina|Metropolitan]]\n* Saint Bishop Leontie of R\u0103d\u0103u\u021bi\n* Benedict Menkes - Romanian biologist\n* [[Dan Pagis]] - Israeli Hebrew poet and literature researcher\n* [[Lothar R\u0103d\u0103ceanu]] -  journalist, linguist, socialist and communist politician\n* [[\u0218tefan Rusu]] - Olympic champion in Greco-Roman wrestling\n* [[Matei Vi\u0219niec]] - Romanian poet and playwright living in France\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Prim\u0103ria din R\u0103d\u0103u\u0163i.jpg|The Town Hall\nFile:Fosta prefectur\u0103 \u0219i hotel, R\u0103d\u0103u\u021bi (3).JPG|Former prefecture building in Union Square\nFile:Colegiul Na\u021bional Eudoxiu Hurmuzachi, R\u0103d\u0103u\u021bi.JPG|Eudoxiu Hurmuzachi High School\nFile:\u0218coala Regina Elisabeta, R\u0103d\u0103u\u021bi.JPG|Queen Elizabaeth Elementary School\nFile:Muzeul de etnografie din Radauti.jpg|The Ethnographic Museum\nFile:Banca din R\u0103d\u0103u\u0163i.jpg|The Romanian Commercial Bank\nFile:60-0383-2 radauti.JPG|CFR train passing through the town\nFile:BogdanI.JPG|Bogdan I Equestrian Statue\nFile:Manastirea Bogdana.jpg|Bogdana Monastery\nFile:Catedrala din R\u0103d\u0103u\u0163i.jpg|The Orthodox Cathedral\nFile:Biserica Na\u015fterea Sfintei Fecioare Maria din R\u0103d\u0103u\u0163i.jpg|The Roman Catholic Church\nFile:Templu151.JPG|The Jewish Temple\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|R\u0103d\u0103u\u021bi}}\n* {{in lang|ro}} [http://primariaradauti.ro/ R\u0103d\u0103u\u0163i Town Hall official site]\n* {{in lang|ro}} [http://www.eradauti.ro/ R\u0103d\u0103u\u0163i Online - Unofficial site]\n* {{in lang|ro}} [http://radauti.info.ro/ R\u0103d\u0103u\u0163i Info - Unofficial site]\n* {{in lang|ro}} [http://cnhurmuzachi.ro/ Eudoxiu Hurmuzachi National High School, R\u0103d\u0103u\u0163i]\n* {{in lang|ro}} [http://www.culturaradauti.ro/ The Cultural Authority of R\u0103d\u0103u\u0163i]\n* {{in lang|ro}} [http://www.bogdana.ro/ Bogdana Monastery official site]\n* {{in lang|ro}} [http://www.radautiziar.ro/ Gazeta de Monitor - Local newspaper about R\u0103d\u0103u\u021bi]\n* {{in lang|ro}} [http://judetulsuceava.ro/localitati/municipii/radauti/ Suceava County site - R\u0103d\u0103u\u021bi web page]\n* {{in lang|ro}} [https://archive.is/20130102235326/http://picasaweb.google.com/EdwardTurJ/OldBukowinaPhotosRadautz Photo Gallery - Old photos of R\u0103d\u0103u\u021bi]\n\n{{Suceava County}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Radauti}}\n[[Category:Cities in Romania]]\n[[Category:Bukovina-German people]]\n[[Category:Jewish communities in Romania]]\n[[Category:Duchy of Bukovina]]\n[[Category:Localities in Southern Bukovina]]\n[[Category:Capitals of former Romanian counties]]\n[[Category:\u021ainutul Suceava]]\n[[Category:Holocaust locations in Romania]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Suceava County]]\n[[Category:R\u0103d\u0103u\u021bi]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the former administrative subdivision of Romania|R\u0103d\u0103u\u021bi County}}\n{{Infobox Romanian subdivision\n|type                   = municipality\n|county                 = Suceava\n|population_total       = auto\n|map_caption            = Location in Suceava County\n|official_name=R\u0103d\u0103u\u021bi\n|image_shield=ROU SV Radauti CoA.png\n|image_map              = Radauti jud Suceava.png\n|image_skyline=Fosta prefectur\u0103 \u0219i hotel, R\u0103d\u0103u\u021bi (2).JPG\n|image_caption=Union Square in downtown R\u0103d\u0103u\u021bi\n|leader_name=Nistor T\u0103tar\n|leader_party=PSD\n|area_total_km2=32.30\n|coordinates            = {{coord|47|50|33|N|25|55|9|E|region:RO|display=inline,title}}\n|website=[http://primariaradauti.ro/ Official site]\n}}\n\n'''R\u0103d\u0103u\u021bi''' ({{IPA-ro|r\u0259d\u0259\u02c8ut\u0361s\u02b2}}; {{lang-de|Radautz}}; {{lang-hu|Rad\u00f3c}}; {{lang-pl|Radowce}}; {{lang-uk|\u0420\u0430\u0434\u0456\u0432\u0446\u0456}}, ''Radivtsi''; {{lang-yi|\u05e8\u05d0\u05b7\u05d3\u05e2\u05f0\u05d9\u05e5}} ''Radevits''; {{lang-tr|Radovi\u00e7e}}) is a [[municipiu|city]] in [[Suceava County]], north-eastern [[Romania]]. It is situated in the historical region of [[Bukovina]]. R\u0103d\u0103u\u021bi is the third largest urban settlement in the county, with a population of 23,822 inhabitants, according to the 2011 census. It was declared a municipality in 1995, along with two other cities in Suceava County: [[F\u0103lticeni]] and [[C\u00e2mpulung Moldovenesc]]. R\u0103d\u0103u\u021bi covers an area of 32,30&nbsp;km\u00b2 and it was the capital of former [[R\u0103d\u0103u\u021bi County]] (until 1950).\n\n==Administration and local politics==\n\n=== Town council ===\n\nThe town's current local council has the following political composition, according to the results of the [[2016 Romanian local elections]]:\n\n{| cellpadding=\"2\" cellspacing=\"0\" border=\"1\" class=\"wikitable\"\n! style=\"background:#ccc\" | &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; \n! style=\"background:#ccc\" | Party\n! style=\"background:#ccc\" | Seats\n! style=\"background:#ccc\" colspan=\"7\" | Current Council\n|-\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PSD}} | &nbsp;\n| [[Social Democratic Party (Romania)|Social Democratic Party (PSD)]]\n| style=\"text-align: right\" | '''7'''\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PSD}} | &nbsp; \n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PSD}} | &nbsp; \n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PSD}} | &nbsp; \n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PSD}} | &nbsp; \n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PSD}} | &nbsp; \n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PSD}} | &nbsp; \n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PSD}} | &nbsp; \n|-\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PNL}} | &nbsp;\n| [[National Liberal Party (Romania)|National Liberal Party (PNL)]]\n| style=\"text-align: right\" | '''5'''\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PNL}} | &nbsp;\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PNL}} | &nbsp;\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PNL}} | &nbsp;\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PNL}} | &nbsp;\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PNL}} | &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n|-\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/ALDE}} | &nbsp;\n| [[Alliance of Liberals and Democrats (Romania)|Alliance of Liberals and Democrats (ALDE)]]\n| style=\"text-align: right\" | '''3'''\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/ALDE}} | &nbsp;\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/ALDE}} | &nbsp;\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/ALDE}} | &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n|-\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PMP}} | &nbsp;\n| [[People's Movement Party|People's Movement Party (PMP)]]\n| style=\"text-align: right\" | '''2'''\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PMP}} | &nbsp;\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/PMP}} | &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n|-\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/Independent}} | &nbsp;\n| [[Independent politician|Union for R\u0103d\u0103u\u021bi (UPR)]]\n| style=\"text-align: right\" | '''2'''\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/Independent}} | &nbsp;\n| {{Romanian politics/party colours/Independent}} | &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n|-\n|}\n\n==Geography==\nR\u0103d\u0103u\u021bi is situated in [[Bukovina]], on a plain between the [[Suceava River|Suceava]] and [[Sucevi\u021ba River|Sucevi\u021ba]] rivers, {{convert|37|km|mi|abbr=on}} north-west from [[Suceava]], the county capital. The city is located in the depression with the same name, at {{convert|375|m|yd|abbr=off}} altitude. It is one of the oldest settlements in Moldavia, known since the 15th century. The towns of [[Siret]], [[Solca]], [[Mili\u0219\u0103u\u021bi]] and [[Vicovu de Sus]] are located relatively close to the city, in the R\u0103d\u0103u\u021bi urban area of influence.\n\n==Demographics==\n{{Historical populations\n|source = Austrian and Romanian census data and/or official estimates\n|1910 |16,535\n|1930 |16,788\n|1948 |14,530\n|1956 |15,949\n|1966 |18,580\n|1977 |21,869\n|1992 |31,074\n|2002 |27,633\n|2011 |23,822\n}}\n\nR\u0103d\u0103u\u0163i reached its peak population in 1992, when more than 31,000 people were living within the city limits. As of 2016, the town of R\u0103d\u0103u\u021bi was the second most populated urban settlement in [[Suceava County]], after the county capital, [[Suceava]].<ref name=\"INSSER2016\">{{cite web|url=http://www.insse.ro/cms/ro/content/popula%C5%A3ia-rom%C3%A2niei-pe-localitati-la-1-ianuarie-2016|title=Popula\u0163ia Rom\u00e2niei pe localitati la 1 ianuarie 2016|date=6 June 2016|accessdate=27 October 2017|publisher=[[National Institute of Statistics (Romania)|INSSE]]|language=Romanian|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171027131447/http://www.insse.ro/cms/ro/content/popula%C5%A3ia-rom%C3%A2niei-pe-localitati-la-1-ianuarie-2016|archive-date=2017-10-27|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nAt the 2011 census, R\u0103d\u0103u\u021bi had a population of 23,822 inhabitants: 96.97% of inhabitants were [[Romanians|ethnic Romanians]], 0.89% [[Russians]] and [[Lipovans]], 0.88% [[Roma in Romania|Roma]], 0.54% [[Ukrainians]] and 0.23% [[Germans of Romania|Germans]] <small>([[Bukovina Germans]])</small>. 83.4% were [[Romanian Orthodox]], 9.1% [[Pentecostal Union of Romania|Pentecostal]], 3.1% [[Roman Catholic]], 0.9% stated they belonged to another religion, 0.8% were [[Romanian Church United with Rome, Greek-Catholic|Greek-Catholic]] and 0.7% each [[Baptist Union of Romania|Baptist]] and [[Lipovan Orthodox Old-Rite Church|Lipovan Orthodox]].\n\n==History==\n[[File:Radautz 1873 Radauti.jpg|thumb|right|150px|Austrian KK stamp, issue 1873, cancelled at ''Radautz'']]\nThe mention of \"Radomir's village\" (as part of a review of [[boyar]] property in the area) in a 1392 document (''uric'') is generally{{who|date=January 2017}} believed to be the town's first mention, and indication of the origin of the name ''R\u0103d\u0103u\u021bi'' (other theories state that the settlement had its origins in earlier periods, and that the name is a [[Slavic languages|Slavic]]-influenced derivative of the [[Latin]] word ''Rottacenum'', as allegedly used by soldiers in the [[Roman Empire|Roman]] garrison in [[Siret]]).<ref>{{cite book | first=Lawrence | last=Winkler | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=F4n4a29AtT4C&pg=PA378&lpg=PA378&dq=Rottacenum&source=bl&ots=wfiDg1iApN&sig=S1rqD6JF0QLxWo1RLJC90v2rQPA&hl=sv&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwim6-ellLjRAhWFWhoKHftuDyc4ChDoAQgYMAA#v=onepage&q=Rottacenum&f=false | title=Between the Cartwheels (Orion's Cartwheels Book 2) | accessdate=January 10, 2017 | website=Google Books | year=2012 | page=378| asin=B009JDN4ES }}</ref>{{unreliable source?|date=January 2017}} The oldest mention of R\u0103d\u0103u\u021bi as such dates from 1413, in a document issued by Moldavian Prince [[Alexandru cel Bun]].\n\nBy the middle of the 14th century, R\u0103d\u0103u\u021bi was already a flourishing settlement, the seat of a prominent [[Eastern Orthodox Church|Eastern Orthodox]] church during the times of [[Bogdan I of Moldova|Bogdan I]] (1359\u20131365), and subsequently a [[Diocese|bishopric]]. Around the St. Nicholas church ([[Bogdana Monastery]]), archaeologists have uncovered a [[Archaeological stratigraphy|habitation layer]] preceding Bogdan's period of rule, one which could point to the existence of a local center prior to the [[foundation of Moldavia]].\n\nAwarded the [[Town privileges|privilege]] of organizing [[fair]]s, R\u0103d\u0103u\u021bi evolved due to its favorable location midway between the [[Carpathian Mountains|Carpathians]] and the tableland area (with traders from both regions establishing contact in the local market). The fairs at R\u0103d\u0103u\u021bi have been dated to the time of [[Stephen III of Moldavia|Stephen the Great]] (a document from 1481; however, since the mention includes details of Stephen's intervention in solving a commercial dispute, it is possible that the fairs were well established by then).\n\nR\u0103d\u0103u\u021bi has a cathedral (built 1402) with the tombs of several Moldavian princes.<ref name=EB1911>{{Cite EB1911 |wstitle=Radautz |volume=22 |page=783}}</ref> R\u0103d\u0103u\u021bi was also the seat of a Greek bishopric, moved to [[Chernivtsi]] in 1786.<ref name=EB1911/>\n\nR\u0103d\u0103u\u021bi was one of the largest cities of the Duchy of [[Bukovina]] during the period of [[Habsburg Monarchy|Habsburg]] administration (1775\u20131918). During that time it saw a high level of [[Germans of Romania|German]] (especially [[Swabians|Swabian]]) immigration.\n\n==Jewish history of R\u0103d\u0103u\u0163i==\n{{main|History of the Jews in Romania}}\nA Jewish community was present before the Habsburg takeover, and is attested to have been overseen by a ''[[starost]]''.\n\nMany Jews fleeing the [[Galicia (Central Europe)|Kingdom of Galicia and Lodomeria]] (as well as other Habsburg areas) from intense persecution and [[anti-Semitism]] during the Middle Ages settled in R\u0103d\u0103u\u0163i. The community was allowed a degree of self-administration, and witnessed a period of prosperity and cultural effervescence during the 19th century.\n\nThe majority of R\u0103d\u0103u\u021bi's Jewish population was exterminated during the [[Holocaust]]. Persecutions became widespread around 1938, when Jews were harassed and attacked by authorities under the [[Octavian Goga]] government; they were confirmed by anti-Semitic legislation passed by the [[Ion Gigurtu]] cabinet, and, in late 1940, exceptionally violent following the establishment of the [[National Legionary State]]. In October 1941, all Jews present in R\u0103d\u0103u\u021bi (more than 10,000) were deported to [[concentration camp]]s in [[Transnistria]].<ref name=\"JEWISH_RADAUTI\">{{cite web | url = http://www.jewishgen.org/yizkor/pinkas_romania/rom2_00516.html | title = Translation of ''R\u0103d\u0103u\u021bi'' chapter from ''Encyclopedia of Jewish Communities in Romania'', Vol. 2 | year = 1980 | accessdate = January 29, 2013 | publisher = Yad Vashem, Jerusalim }}</ref>\n\n==Bogdana Monastery==\nThe Princely Church at R\u0103d\u0103u\u0163i contained the graves of [[Bogdan I]] and his son [[La\u0163cu]], both [[Voivode]]s/[[Prince]]s of [[Moldavia]], as well as a later ruler, [[Roman I of Moldavia]]. Is the oldest monastery from [[Moldova]] and [[Bucovina]] (1365). Inside the monastery there are 14 tombs (like Bogdan I (1359\u20131365), La\u021bcu Voievod (1365\u20131373), Roman I (1391\u20131394), \u0218tefan I (1394\u20131399), Bogdan, the brother Alexandru cel Bun, Bogdan, son of Alexandru cel Bun and others.\n\n== Twin towns \u2014 Sister cities ==\n\nR\u0103d\u0103u\u021bi is [[Twin towns and sister cities|twinned]] with:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://primariaradauti.ro/radauti/orase-infratite/|title=Prim\u0103ria R\u0103d\u0103u\u021bi - Ora\u0219e \u00eenfr\u0103\u021bite (in Romanian)|work=Prim\u0103ria R\u0103d\u0103u\u021bi}}</ref>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|\n* {{flagicon|DEU}} [[Beilstein, W\u00fcrttemberg|Beilstein]], [[Germany]]\n* {{flagicon|FRA}} [[Pontault-Combault]], [[France]]\n* {{flagicon|MDA}} [[Drochia]], [[Moldova]]\n* {{flagicon|MDA}} [[Briceni]], [[Moldova]]\n* {{flagicon|POR}} [[Caminha]], [[Portugal]]\n* {{flagicon|POL}} [[Gliwice]], [[Poland]]\n* {{flagicon|CYP}} [[Kyrenia]], [[Cyprus]]\n* {{flagicon|ITA}} [[Ragusa, Sicily|Ragusa]], [[Italy]]\n|}\n\n==Natives==\n* [[Avigdor Arikha]] - Israeli painter\n* [[Emil Armin]] - American artist \n* [[Alexandru Bodnar]] - athlete\n* [[Heinrich G\u00e4rtner (cinematographer)|Heinrich G\u00e4rtner]] - cinematographer\n* [[Irina Lauric]] - sprint canoeist\n* Iacov Putneanul - [[Metropolitan of Moldavia and Bukovina|Metropolitan]]\n* Saint Bishop Leontie of R\u0103d\u0103u\u021bi\n* Benedict Menkes - Romanian biologist\n* [[Dan Pagis]] - Israeli Hebrew poet and literature researcher\n* [[Lothar R\u0103d\u0103ceanu]] -  journalist, linguist, socialist and communist politician\n* [[\u0218tefan Rusu]] - Olympic champion in Greco-Roman wrestling\n* [[Matei Vi\u0219niec]] - Romanian poet and playwright living in France\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Prim\u0103ria din R\u0103d\u0103u\u0163i.jpg|The Town Hall\nFile:Fosta prefectur\u0103 \u0219i hotel, R\u0103d\u0103u\u021bi (3).JPG|Former prefecture building in Union Square\nFile:Colegiul Na\u021bional Eudoxiu Hurmuzachi, R\u0103d\u0103u\u021bi.JPG|Eudoxiu Hurmuzachi High School\nFile:\u0218coala Regina Elisabeta, R\u0103d\u0103u\u021bi.JPG|Queen Elizabaeth Elementary School\nFile:Muzeul de etnografie din Radauti.jpg|The Ethnographic Museum\nFile:Banca din R\u0103d\u0103u\u0163i.jpg|The Romanian Commercial Bank\nFile:60-0383-2 radauti.JPG|CFR train passing through the town\nFile:BogdanI.JPG|Bogdan I Equestrian Statue\nFile:Manastirea Bogdana.jpg|Bogdana Monastery\nFile:Catedrala din R\u0103d\u0103u\u0163i.jpg|The Orthodox Cathedral\nFile:Biserica Na\u015fterea Sfintei Fecioare Maria din R\u0103d\u0103u\u0163i.jpg|The Roman Catholic Church\nFile:Templu151.JPG|The Jewish Temple\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|R\u0103d\u0103u\u021bi}}\n* {{in lang|ro}} [http://primariaradauti.ro/ R\u0103d\u0103u\u0163i Town Hall official site]\n* {{in lang|ro}} [http://www.eradauti.ro/ R\u0103d\u0103u\u0163i Online - Unofficial site]\n* {{in lang|ro}} [http://radauti.info.ro/ R\u0103d\u0103u\u0163i Info - Unofficial site]\n* {{in lang|ro}} [http://cnhurmuzachi.ro/ Eudoxiu Hurmuzachi National High School, R\u0103d\u0103u\u0163i]\n* {{in lang|ro}} [http://www.culturaradauti.ro/ The Cultural Authority of R\u0103d\u0103u\u0163i]\n* {{in lang|ro}} [http://www.bogdana.ro/ Bogdana Monastery official site]\n* {{in lang|ro}} [http://www.radautiziar.ro/ Gazeta de Monitor - Local newspaper about R\u0103d\u0103u\u021bi]\n* {{in lang|ro}} [http://judetulsuceava.ro/localitati/municipii/radauti/ Suceava County site - R\u0103d\u0103u\u021bi web page]\n* {{in lang|ro}} [https://archive.is/20130102235326/http://picasaweb.google.com/EdwardTurJ/OldBukowinaPhotosRadautz Photo Gallery - Old photos of R\u0103d\u0103u\u021bi]\n\n{{Suceava County}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Radauti}}\n[[Category:Cities in Romania]]\n[[Category:Bukovina-German people]]\n[[Category:Jewish communities in Romania]]\n[[Category:Duchy of Bukovina]]\n[[Category:Localities in Southern Bukovina]]\n[[Category:Capitals of former Romanian counties]]\n[[Category:\u021ainutul Suceava]]\n[[Category:Holocaust locations in Romania]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Suceava County]]\n[[Category:R\u0103d\u0103u\u021bi]]\n", "name_user": "Markussep", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/R%C4%83d%C4%83u%C8%9Bi"}
{"title_page": "Fuck You (magazine)", "text_new": "\n\n\n\nThis a personal Shibal, Ebat,Fick Dich, Vaffancula and Fuck off to all using Wikipedia like this for Christian terrorism. I am fed up with some free encyclopedia for creative commons thats being used as a GPL to ruin lives. Start wars and infringe on peoples copywrite. \n\n\n\n\n{{Infobox magazine\n| title = Fuck You\n| image_file = \n| image_size = \n| image_caption = \n| editor = [[Ed Sanders]]\n| frequency = \n| circulation = \n| category = [[Avant-garde]]\n| company = \n| publisher = Ed Sanders\n| firstdate = February/April 1962\n| finaldate = 1965\n| finalnumber = 13\n| country = [[United States]]\n| language = [[English language|English]]\n| website = \n| issn = \n}}\n'''''Fuck You: A Magazine of the Arts''''' was a [[literary magazine]] founded in 1962 by the poet [[Ed Sanders]]<ref>{{cite news|author=Laura Martisiute|title=10 Cool Magazines From The Past You\u2019ll Want To Get Your Hands On|url=http://listverse.com/2015/12/28/10-cool-magazines-from-the-past-youll-want-to-get-your-hands-on/|accessdate=December 9, 2016|work=Listverse|date=December 28, 2015}}</ref>  on the [[Lower East Side]] of New York City. Sanders later co-founded the musical group [[the Fugs]]. Sanders produced thirteen issues of ''Fuck You: A Magazine of the Arts'' from 1962 to 1965.<ref name=\"Haralson2014\">{{cite book|author=Eric L. Haralson|title=Encyclopedia of American Poetry: The Twentieth Century|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=noCrAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA402|accessdate=December 4, 2015|date=January 21, 2014|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-317-76322-2|page=402}}</ref>\n\nThe credo for the magazine, originated by Sanders, was ''I'll print anything.'' Its first issue contained the following dedication: \"Dedicated to [[Pacifism]], [[Unilateral disarmament|Unilateral Disarmament]], [[National security|National Defense]] thru [[Nonviolent resistance|Nonviolent Resistence]] [sic], Multilateral Indiscriminate Apertural Conjugation, [[Anarchism]], [[World Federalism]], [[Civil Disobedience]], Obstructers & Submarine Boarders, and All Those [[Groping|Groped]] by [[J. Edgar Hoover]] in the Silent Halls of Congress.\"<ref name=\"no1\">{{cite journal|url=http://cdn.realitystudio.org/images/bibliographic_bunker/fuck_you/fuck-you-press-pdfs/fuck-you.01.pdf|title=Fuck You/A Magazine of the Arts|number=1|accessdate=June 28, 2015}}</ref>\n\n''Fuck You: A Magazine of the Arts'' was produced on a [[mimeograph]] and printed on multi-colored [[construction paper]].\n\n==Legacy==\n''Fuck You: A Magazine of the Arts'' was a core publication in the [[Mimeo Revolution]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://realitystudio.org/bibliographic-bunker/fuck-you-press-archive/ |title=RealityStudio website: Fuck You Press Archive|work=Reality Studio|accessdate=June 24, 2012}}</ref> It was dedicated to [[free expression]], and especially defying the [[taboo]]s around sex and drugs, advocating free love [[promiscuity]] and the use of [[psychedelics]] long before those were picked up by the more widespread countercultural movements of the late Sixties. Ed Sanders and his collaborators served as a bridge between the [[Beat generation]] of the Fifties and the later [[Hippie]] [[counterculture]] of the mid Sixties.\n\n==List of issues==\n#Number 1 (Feb/April 1962)\n#Number 2 (May 1962)\n#Number 3 (June 1962)\n#Number 4 (August 1962)\n#Number 5, Volume 1 (Dec 1962)\n#Number 5, Volume 2 (Dec 1962)\n#Number 5, Volume 3 (May 1963)\n#Number 5, Volume 4 (??? 1963)\n#Number 5, Volume 5 (Dec 1963)\n#Number 5, Volume 6 (April/May 1964)\n#Number 5, Volume 7 (Sept 1964)\n#Number 5, Volume 8 (1965)\u2014''Mad Motherfucker Issue'' ([[Andy Warhol]] cover)\n#Number 5, Volume 9 (June 1965)\n\n==Participants==<!-- New links in alphabetical order please -->\nIssues included works by:\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n*[[Antonin Artaud]]\n*[[W. H. Auden]]\n*[[Julian Beck]]\n*[[Ted Berrigan]]\n*[[Joe Brainard]]\n*[[William S. Burroughs]]\n*[[Gregory Corso]]\n*[[Robert Creeley]]\n*[[Diane DiPrima]]\n*[[Allen Ginsberg]]\n*[[Herbert Huncke]]\n*[[Leroi Jones]]\n*[[Tuli Kupferberg]]\n*[[Norman Mailer]]\n*[[Michael McClure]]\n*[[Charles Olson]]\n*[[Frank O'Hara]]\n*[[Peter Orlovsky]]\n*[[Gary Snyder]]\n*[[Andy Warhol]]\n*[[Philip Whalen]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n;Notes\n{{Reflist}}\n\n;Bibliography\n*[http://realitystudio.org/bibliographic-bunker/fuck-you-press-archive/ ''Fuck You'' web archive]\n*''Life Magazine'' (February 17, 1967).\n*Charters, Ann (ed.). ''The Portable Beat Reader''. New York: [[Penguin Books]], 1992. {{ISBN|0-670-83885-3}} (hc); {{ISBN|0-14-015102-8}} (pbk).\n*Sanders, Ed. ''Fug You: An Informal History of the Peace Eye Bookstore, the Fuck You Press, the Fugs, and Counterculture in the Lower East Side'', Da Capo Press, 2011\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.ubu.com/vp/FuckYou.html Archive of ''Fuck You: A Magazine of the Arts''] at [[Ubuweb]]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070224133754/http://www.verdantpress.com/fuckyou.html ''Fuck You: A Magazine of the Arts''] at Verdant Press\n*[http://www.worldcat.org/oclc/2220952 ''Fuck You: A Magazine of the Arts'' library holdings] in WorldCat\n\n[[Category:1962 establishments in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:1965 disestablishments in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:American art]]\n[[Category:American arts magazines]]\n[[Category:American poetry magazines]]\n[[Category:Defunct American literary magazines]]\n[[Category:Lower East Side]]\n[[Category:Magazines published in New York City]]\n[[Category:Magazines established in 1962]]\n[[Category:Magazines disestablished in 1965]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox magazine\n| title = Fuck You\n| image_file = \n| image_size = \n| image_caption = \n| editor = [[Ed Sanders]]\n| frequency = \n| circulation = \n| category = [[Avant-garde]]\n| company = \n| publisher = Ed Sanders\n| firstdate = February/April 1962\n| finaldate = 1965\n| finalnumber = 13\n| country = [[United States]]\n| language = [[English language|English]]\n| website = \n| issn = \n}}\n'''''Fuck You: A Magazine of the Arts''''' was a [[literary magazine]] founded in 1962 by the poet [[Ed Sanders]]<ref>{{cite news|author=Laura Martisiute|title=10 Cool Magazines From The Past You\u2019ll Want To Get Your Hands On|url=http://listverse.com/2015/12/28/10-cool-magazines-from-the-past-youll-want-to-get-your-hands-on/|accessdate=December 9, 2016|work=Listverse|date=December 28, 2015}}</ref>  on the [[Lower East Side]] of New York City. Sanders later co-founded the musical group [[the Fugs]]. Sanders produced thirteen issues of ''Fuck You: A Magazine of the Arts'' from 1962 to 1965.<ref name=\"Haralson2014\">{{cite book|author=Eric L. Haralson|title=Encyclopedia of American Poetry: The Twentieth Century|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=noCrAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA402|accessdate=December 4, 2015|date=January 21, 2014|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-317-76322-2|page=402}}</ref>\n\nThe credo for the magazine, originated by Sanders, was ''I'll print anything.'' Its first issue contained the following dedication: \"Dedicated to [[Pacifism]], [[Unilateral disarmament|Unilateral Disarmament]], [[National security|National Defense]] thru [[Nonviolent resistance|Nonviolent Resistence]] [sic], Multilateral Indiscriminate Apertural Conjugation, [[Anarchism]], [[World Federalism]], [[Civil Disobedience]], Obstructers & Submarine Boarders, and All Those [[Groping|Groped]] by [[J. Edgar Hoover]] in the Silent Halls of Congress.\"<ref name=\"no1\">{{cite journal|url=http://cdn.realitystudio.org/images/bibliographic_bunker/fuck_you/fuck-you-press-pdfs/fuck-you.01.pdf|title=Fuck You/A Magazine of the Arts|number=1|accessdate=June 28, 2015}}</ref>\n\n''Fuck You: A Magazine of the Arts'' was produced on a [[mimeograph]] and printed on multi-colored [[construction paper]].\n\n==Legacy==\n''Fuck You: A Magazine of the Arts'' was a core publication in the [[Mimeo Revolution]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://realitystudio.org/bibliographic-bunker/fuck-you-press-archive/ |title=RealityStudio website: Fuck You Press Archive|work=Reality Studio|accessdate=June 24, 2012}}</ref> It was dedicated to [[free expression]], and especially defying the [[taboo]]s around sex and drugs, advocating free love [[promiscuity]] and the use of [[psychedelics]] long before those were picked up by the more widespread countercultural movements of the late Sixties. Ed Sanders and his collaborators served as a bridge between the [[Beat generation]] of the Fifties and the later [[Hippie]] [[counterculture]] of the mid Sixties.\n\n==List of issues==\n#Number 1 (Feb/April 1962)\n#Number 2 (May 1962)\n#Number 3 (June 1962)\n#Number 4 (August 1962)\n#Number 5, Volume 1 (Dec 1962)\n#Number 5, Volume 2 (Dec 1962)\n#Number 5, Volume 3 (May 1963)\n#Number 5, Volume 4 (??? 1963)\n#Number 5, Volume 5 (Dec 1963)\n#Number 5, Volume 6 (April/May 1964)\n#Number 5, Volume 7 (Sept 1964)\n#Number 5, Volume 8 (1965)\u2014''Mad Motherfucker Issue'' ([[Andy Warhol]] cover)\n#Number 5, Volume 9 (June 1965)\n\n==Participants==<!-- New links in alphabetical order please -->\nIssues included works by:\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n*[[Antonin Artaud]]\n*[[W. H. Auden]]\n*[[Julian Beck]]\n*[[Ted Berrigan]]\n*[[Joe Brainard]]\n*[[William S. Burroughs]]\n*[[Gregory Corso]]\n*[[Robert Creeley]]\n*[[Diane DiPrima]]\n*[[Allen Ginsberg]]\n*[[Herbert Huncke]]\n*[[Leroi Jones]]\n*[[Tuli Kupferberg]]\n*[[Norman Mailer]]\n*[[Michael McClure]]\n*[[Charles Olson]]\n*[[Frank O'Hara]]\n*[[Peter Orlovsky]]\n*[[Gary Snyder]]\n*[[Andy Warhol]]\n*[[Philip Whalen]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n;Notes\n{{Reflist}}\n\n;Bibliography\n*[http://realitystudio.org/bibliographic-bunker/fuck-you-press-archive/ ''Fuck You'' web archive]\n*''Life Magazine'' (February 17, 1967).\n*Charters, Ann (ed.). ''The Portable Beat Reader''. New York: [[Penguin Books]], 1992. {{ISBN|0-670-83885-3}} (hc); {{ISBN|0-14-015102-8}} (pbk).\n*Sanders, Ed. ''Fug You: An Informal History of the Peace Eye Book